commit_message:
Make libvirt migration security configurable

Adding flags to choose between tls/tcp connections as well as
sasl/none authentication when configuring libvirt migration.

This allows to deploy proper libvirt security in combination with
the nova::compute class.

Change-Id: Ib479a1f4cd2df0d55347ed71fb8f0ab69aaeceef
(cherry picked from commit 1383cee7d46c5c6b6c83bed194822c846b10782d)

commit_message:
Remove --tenant suggestion for flavor-access-list

when help flavor-access-list, nova client tells user to
try --tenant while try with it , nova client tells user
it's not implemented. We should avoid this kind of suggestion.

Change-Id: Ia35f9d35d6c4855122385de2a5cc013fcba1f126

commit_message:
Modify unbound script executable

This patch modifies the permission of usr/libexec/kuryr/unbound and
makes it executable.

Change-Id: I7f898763a45b9ee09d3876df73836df13d1bea4c
Signed-off-by: Taku Fukushima <f.tac.mac@gmail.com>
Closes-Bug: #1516871

commit_message:
Fix gate-fuel-docs-docs CI job

* Add tox.ini, setup.cfg and setup.py to allow docs building
using tox and setuptools
* Set doc/build as an output dir in setup.cfg to allow doc
publishing by gate-fuel-docs-docs job
* Add '.tox' and '*egg' paths to exclude_patterns in conf.py
* Add stub index.rst with basic info and link to the web verstion
of the docs to fix building of manpages
* Add '.tox' dir to .gitignore

Change-Id: Iaec750d6035bd0e30c10a12142be35514df1fb15
(cherry picked from commit 7218dfecd59b6de18405b42e756b1de2e1d0c8b6)

commit_message:
Handle DB failures in servicegroup DB driver

Fix an issue where when local conductor is used, the DB driver for
servicegroup will not handle transient DB problems gracefully.  The
patch makes the behavior consistent with messaging timeouts if remote
conductor is used.

Change-Id: Ie736e7b64ea4f60f78878c8713ce826702f9f05e
Closes-Bug: 1505471

commit_message:
Fix gate-fuel-docs-docs CI job

* Add tox.ini, setup.cfg and setup.py to allow docs building
using tox and setuptools
* Set doc/build as an output dir in setup.cfg to allow doc
publishing by gate-fuel-docs-docs job
* Add '.tox' and '*egg' paths to exclude_patterns in conf.py
* Add '.tox' dir to .gitignore
Change-Id: Iaec750d6035bd0e30c10a12142be35514df1fb15
(cherry picked from commit 7218dfecd59b6de18405b42e756b1de2e1d0c8b6)

commit_message:
Drop direct engine support

This change remove support of direct engine in Sahara.
Unit tests related to direct engine were removed.

Implements blueprint: remove-direct-engine

Change-Id: Iba292996dd052a069a98f1024441255a15c0f734

Build Kernel Modules for OVS

Currently we are building OVS from sources in the dragonflow devstack installation.
We did not compile the modules and did not install them

commit_message:
Use search_ext_s instead of search_s in ldap

Usage of search_ext_s will allow us to use sizelimit parameter to
truncate too long list of results.

Change-Id: I670ba40c6d1700a9e57f4a29cb4c8d350572953d
Partial-Bug: 1501698

commit_message:
Add sort_dir/key to flavor list

'marker' and 'limit' are already added to flavor list, but 'sort_key'
and 'sort_dir' which are useful for pagination are missing.

Closes-bug: #1505939
Change-Id: Id78595f15fbb289133092a32238238e3c4a9d0a0

commit_message:
Add pagination params for flavor list

Mission 'marker' and 'limit' params for `nova flavor-list` shell
command. It would be nice to have this when there are many flavors.

Change-Id: I4579b63bc6c711f1b5eaf07b54d393ebcbfd8277
Closes-bug: #1505874

commit_message:
Make node status value translatable

In the node table the value of status column is not
translatable. this patch adding a display choices tuple
with translatable option.

Closes-Bug: #1517410

Change-Id: I61cf8a2004985c877e992e798aaa8cca63de5784

commit_message:
Update CLI reference for python-ironicclient 1.0.0

Following two subcommands are added

<term><command>node-get-vendor-passthru-methods</command></term>
    Get the vendor passthru methods for a node.
<term><command>driver-get-vendor-passthru-methods</command></term>
    Get the vendor passthru methods for a driver.

Change-Id: I33d109717827aaa0e82733e0972bfce1c6005e04

commit_message:
Make cluster status value translatable

In the cluster table the value of status column is not
translatable. this patch adding a display choices tuple
with translatable option.

Change-Id: I68e892d03f876d2bda27bd17a0408d983523d7b9
Closes-Bug: #1517425

commit_message:
Resync L3, DHCP and OVS/LB agents upon revival

In big and busy clusters there could be a condition when
rabbitmq clustering mechanism synchronizes queues and during
this period agents connected to that instance of rabbitmq
can't communicate with the server and server considers them
dead moving resources away. After agent become active again,
it needs to cleanup state entries and synchronize its state
with neutron-server.
The solution is to make agents aware of their state from
neutron-server point of view. This is done by changing state
reports from cast to call that would return agent's status.
When agent was dead and becomes alive, it would receive special
AGENT_REVIVED status indicating that it should refresh its
local data which it would not do otherwise.

Closes-Bug: #1505166
Change-Id: Id28248f4f75821fbacf46e2c44e40f27f59172a9

[{'created': '2015-09-08 16:29:49.000000000', 'message': "Allow naming of custom types

It is useful to be able to create custom config types, however when this
is done the output file lists the config as 'unknown type'.

Current behaviour example:

    PORT_TYPE = types.Integer(1, 65535)
    cfg.Opt('port', type=config.PORT_TYPE, default=9511,
            help='The port for the API server.')

Generates:

    # The port for the API server. (unknown type)
    # Minimum value: 1
    # Maximum value: 65535
    #port = 9511

This change uses the type name from the type and also allows
customisation. The last code block will now generate 'integer value'
rather than 'unknown type'. The type name can also be overridden:

    PORT_TYPE = types.Integer(1, 65535, type_name='port number')

Generates:

    # The port for the API server. (port number)
    # Minimum value: 1
    # Maximum value: 65535
    #port = 9511

Change-Id: I0a58c613a958ac00dc2cecacc4898df5390cd301

commit_message:
Allow naming of custom types

It is useful to be able to create custom config types, however when this
is done the output file lists the config as 'unknown type'.

Current behaviour example:

    PORT_TYPE = types.Integer(1, 65535)
    cfg.Opt('port', type=PORT_TYPE, default=9511,
            help='The port for the API server.')

Generates:

    # The port for the API server. (unknown type)
    # Minimum value: 1
    # Maximum value: 65535
    #port = 9511

This change uses the type name from the type and also allows
customisation. The last code block will now generate 'integer value'
rather than 'unknown type'. The type name can also be overridden:

    PORT_TYPE = types.Integer(1, 65535, type_name='port number')

Generates:

    # The port for the API server. (port number)
    # Minimum value: 1
    # Maximum value: 65535
    #port = 9511

Closes-Bug: #1502062
Change-Id: I0a58c613a958ac00dc2cecacc4898df5390cd301

commit_message:
Fix alarm-updated message for the python API

The tenantId field in the alarm-updated message for the python API
was named tenant_id. This caused a NullPointerException in the
Threshold Engine since tenantId wasn't set.

This the smoke test to get farther. It now fails trying to
check alarm history.

Change-Id: I3cc507b03178410a47bc72f4859e41310abf411b

commit_message:
Add ability to override class parameters

This patch implements functionality to override
hardcoded variables of 'params' class.
Now all parameters for package/service names
and other packaging specific stuff can be
overridden using 'globals' class.
This can be very useful if users don't want
to rely on RDO or UCA packaging or they may want
to use their specific (alternative) packages with
their characterized names, paths, configs and so on.

(3 comments)

The last set of comments I found inline makes me quite disappointed whit the whole idea of putting a code change to a public review. 

This change adds the functionality which as far as I know is unique to Rally. There is no other automated tool in OpenStack that allows to collect the performance data from Hadoop running in a cloud and I doubt that a user without Hadoop expertise will be able to reach those results manually. 

However it looks like the reviewers pay more attention to how the code looks rather than what it does and why. The people do make mistakes in their changes and they should be pointed with a -1 review, no doubts. But why a -1 for such minor things like a letter in a doc-string? A -1 mark has become a very strong sign that something is wrong with the change and while a -1 is in the list other reviewers just ignore the change. They just don't want to spend their time on the change that is already marked wrong by someone else. And that's a pretty efficient approach from my point of view.

But the most disappointing  in all of that is that when I started digging deeper into the stuff that was "wrong" in my change I found out that if fact it is not. It is not wrong to use @static method when a class reference is not required. It is not wrong to use ":return" because Sphinx allows and handles both. And the pep257 check has not failed.

I just can't see the point why someone would block the change with comment like "replace this with that" and does not even provide a reason WHY?

I have no intent to offend anyone. But I have never expected to get this kind of attitude to the code change.'}, {'account_id': 13609, 'date': '2015-09-10 15:06:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

- change is 2 months old and still on review
- Rally was radically changed few times without backward compatibility during this time frame and nobody announced this in advance to Nikita in these changes
- core team is not moderating the reviews coming to the changes appropriately. Comments by Alex M. in most of the cases make no sense and moreover it's not the reason either to set -1 or not to review the change by other reviewers.

I would recommend Boris P. and team to refactor the overall reviewing process to become more welcoming to the external contributors and more strict to the reviews quality."}, {'account_id': 13609, 'date': '2015-09-19 04:22:54.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 13609, 'date': '2015-09-19 04:26:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

commit_message:
[Sahara] Add Hadoop metrics collection

Sahara Job benchmarks can now collect information from Hadoop's
Historyserver.

All job benchmarks can now declare required metrics in the
hadoop_metrics property. The expected format is list of strings
<group_name>:<counter_name>.

Change-Id: I9e3900f65beef0fcba9538fca2bd650bfad16345

Thanks for the comments.

I agree it looks a bit complicated, but there is a reason for that. Python 2 will try to convert everything to ascii when printing or logging unless it is told not to do so. When python 2 sees a non-ascii symbol it crashes so my original intention was to fix that. 

But then comes python 3 which is able to log unicode properly but what it really does is converting unicode to ascii in \x<whatever> way. The request does not crash. But imagine what the log looks like if you are uploading 5Gb image or any other file and it is being logged. So that's why it is not a good idea to allow python 3 log unicode that does not decode to ascii as well.

I'm not sure that this is the best solution, but is instance(data, six.text_type) will not help in python3 case I guess."}, {'account_id': 11022, 'date': '2015-05-28 14:36:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Hi Nikita, great catch.

According to Six docs, the lib should cover both Python 2 and 3, but you might need check for both https://pythonhosted.org/six/#six.text_type and https://pythonhosted.org/six/#six.string_types'}, {'account_id': 7132, 'date': '2015-05-29 11:33:57.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-29 14:40:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified+1

commit_message:
Fix logging of binary contentent in request

The request body may contain binary file which will lead
to the logging failure. The request logging is wrapped with
try:except to prevent that.

Change-Id: I844af54ec93d99636ea68ba07f48dae10368de8a
Closes-Bug: #1453953

commit_message:
Use physnet mapping for the default floating network

The default floating network should be created with 'flat' type and has mapping
to a bridge, so in case of adding additional external network it will be still
operational

Change-Id: I7c1d20c7aa00b6829fffa82c46a05bc577fe88f2
Closes-bug: #1489718

commit_message:
Convert creation_time to string

The message to be serialized to JSON has a creation_time field
that is of datetime type. The json.dumps method is unable to
serialize this. Changing creation_time to timestamp based on
review comments and to keep it consistent with monasca-api.

Change-Id: Ibbff895e545788cb64b8733adcd6d060f11ef6c0

Drop outdated sqlite downgrade script

There is still one downgrade script for sqlite.
As openstack dosen't support downgrade script
now, remove it to avoid confusion.

commit_message:
tox.ini: check migrations for the subproject only

There is no need to check all migrations from all installed migration
entrypoints available on the system as part of pep8 check.

Change-Id: Id2ca40eb7a287d0919dac8e98801cc2324873a25

commit_message:
get_running_processes: don't list 'kernel' as a pid

fuser shows some of kernel accesses (mount points, swap files, etc)
using the string 'kernel' as a pid. Ignore such a pseudo-pid to
avoid the spurious errors and noise in the logs.

Change-Id: I5e99cff3218388468660770c2e304494023a9099

[{'created': '2015-11-16 08:35:15.000000000', 'message': 'Fix project_id in API sample docs

project_id is generated with uuid.uuid4().hex in Keystone and the
format is uuid4 without hyphens.
However the API sample docs contain different format values, then
it makes readers confused. This patch changes these project_ids to
valid format values.

Change-Id: I0660d52a26c76366691a7b990baad8aee320ea95
'}]
commit_message:
Fix project_id in API sample docs

project_id is generated with uuid.uuid4().hex in Keystone and the
format is uuid4 without hyphens.
However the API sample docs contain different format values, then
it makes readers confused. This patch changes these project_ids to
valid format values.

Change-Id: I0660d52a26c76366691a7b990baad8aee320ea95

commit_message:
Add documentation on how to run tests

Added a testing page to the documentation.

This includes information on:
 * Running PEP8 checks
 * Running unit tests
 * Running functional tests

Closes-bug:#1511731
Change-Id: I4a5cf4be98f32455e36ea7d6a45b18afca043809

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code

commit_message:
update node shell help info

node-delete help info show "Unregister a node from the Ironic service"
but it supports to deleting one or more nodes, so change to node(s).

Change-Id: I634a113b8476088235ee08950553bdfc10667c5f

commit_message:
Refactor the image download and checksum computation bits

Prior to this patch downloading and computing the checksum of the image
were done in different stages, after the download the file would need
to be re-read and the checksum was computed. This patch is changing it
by creating a ImageDownload class which computes the checksum at the same
time the image is being downloaded, this saves time and also make the
code more portable.

Related-Bug: #1505685
Change-Id: I71f9f2bd9a62a6a6cc474d0ae519591cea6381d6

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-19 10:53:07.000000000', 'message': "Add clean up method for the DHCP factory

The DHCP provider base class has only update methods to notify the
provider which DHCP BOOT options to reserve when a node comes up. If anyone
wants to create his own DHCP provider implementation for Ironic, none of
the base class methods get triggered after a node is deleted, so the DHCP
reservations will be present even after the Ironic node is deleted.

This patch adds a 'clean_dhcp' method to the DHCPFactory class, which is used
to clean the DHCP BOOT options when an Ironic node is deleted. This is called
when an Ironic node is torn down.

Closes-Bug: #1498923
Change-Id: Iba681f7f19b3621de70c9464fb484af0b9358ddd
"}]
commit_message:
Add clean up method for the DHCP factory

The DHCP provider base class has only update methods to notify the
provider which DHCP BOOT options to reserve when a node comes up. If anyone
wants to create his own DHCP provider implementation for Ironic, none of
the base class methods get triggered after a node is deleted, so the DHCP
reservations will be present even after the Ironic node is deleted.

This patch adds a 'clean_dhcp' method to the DHCPFactory class, which is used
to clean the DHCP BOOT options when an Ironic node is deleted. This is called
when an Ironic node is torn down.

Closes-Bug: #1498923
Change-Id: Iba681f7f19b3621de70c9464fb484af0b9358ddd

Add do_mkbootstrap entry point

* New entry point, which adds possibility to create console_script
  with native setup.py

commit_message:
Enable standard python jobs for pymod2pkg

As decided in the last RPM Packaging irc meeting (see
https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/openstack-rpm-packaging), we'd
like to have standard checks/gatings for pymod2pks reviews.

commit_message:
Don't add default route to HA router if there is no gateway ip

When adding an external network with no gateway ip to a HA router,
l3 agent will report exception. The exception comes from the code
of adding default route to HA router. However, if there is no
gateway ip in the external network, there is no need to add such
route.

Closes-Bug: #1515209
(cherry picked from commit 14c09fdfc4fbda874508c170ac6a7d6ead0bfd2e)

Conflicts:
	neutron/agent/l3/ha_router.py

Change-Id: I41d6a292c903758f408d3d93a64dca7adeeb5769

commit_message:
Add non-voting constraints jobs to nova

Adds all needed -constraints jobs to nova's check queue as non-voting

Depends-On: Icbbb78cfcd074b0050e60c54557637af723f9b92
Implements Blueprint: Requirements-Management

Change-Id: I637b432db425c8d706865b0c85fc7b5bd06bcc99

commit_message:
remove oslo-incubator jobs

We are removing all the code and tests from oslo-incubator.
previously we used oslo-incubator as a common code repository,
we are going to stop doing that now.
http://markmail.org/message/kgdnukenoni3hbmw

Change-Id: Id2dd8362abf8df8b1e8864cbd8450effd5734ebd

commit_message:
Catch InvalidImageStatusTransition error

Now, when delete image to unallowed status, it will raise a 500
error. So we should catch that error to avoid it.

Change-Id: I47f777a81a6069793dfa4d52eace79edb266669d
Closes-bug: #1505474

commit_message:
Add python-searchlightclient repo

Adds a repo for python-searchlightclient. ACL groups exist already;
the pypi project exists and is set up with openstackci as an owner.
Git repo does not yet exist.

Partial blueprint: openstack-client-search-initial-plugin

Change-Id: I0e64d7eb5502c280177d0d02288509b1724efb08

an authentication plugin related options

commit_message:
Allow to customize vagrant deployment

Extract the Vagrantfile configuration to a Vagrantfile.custom file, to
permit easy customization of the Vagrant deployment without the need to
modify a file under version control.

Closes-Bug: #1517475
Change-Id: I03e3ef373ec47e3d622b77fa9cf88748db99adaa

commit_message:
Factor out definition of nodes in Vagrantfile

All the nodes, with the exception of the operator, are build the same
with maybe different specs. We can remove the duplication with a bit of
metaprogramming.

Also pass all expected arguments to the provisionning script,and get
rid of hardcoded path to it.

Closes-Bug: #1517476

Change-Id: I515ef1d529d7ec49038662001a3e5345a941fea7

commit_message:
Add #openstack-meeting-cp to eavesdrop

The TC recently decided to create a new space for cross projects
discussions/ meetings.  This channel is deliberately granted the ability
to run meetings.  The social contract for this will largley be monitored
by reviewers in irc-meetings

Change-Id: I8a2c81ea435080eae8d16efe41a55b5d982489f9

commit_message:
PoC: Generate API docs from tempest.log

tempest-lib's RestClient writes the detail of rest operation(http code,
URI, request body, response body) to tempest.log, and it is possible to
generate API docs from the log.
This is a prototype for that.

The implementation steps are following:
 1. Insert start/end messages for each API operation to tempest.log (Done)
 2. Create a script for parsing tempest.log and converting useful format
 3. Make test operation serial(not parallel) for avoiding conflict of
    start/end messages
 4. Make the docstring of service client method consistent because it will
    be used for the overview of each API
 5. Add the combinations of both "service client module path(tempest.
    services.compute, etc)" and "service name(compute, etc.)".

TODO: Define useful format which is generated from this feature

By step 1, tempest.log is written like:
 [..] Start of API log [compute: Delete server]
 [..] Request (ServersTestJSON:tearDownClass): 204 DELETE
      http://192.168.11.65:8774/v2.1/c6068bb3e401470cb028bf32ca7a5100/servers/1d54c68f-66ef-4c59-9d3a-8401c0512bf7 0.511s
 [..] Request - Headers: {'Content-Type': 'application/json',
         'Accept': 'application/json', 'X-Auth-Token': '<omitted>'}
         Body: None
 [..] Response - Headers: {'status': '204', 'content-length': '0',
         'x-compute-request-id': 'req-ce5cc4f4-fad1-40a0-9396-a24f3ab91995',
         'vary': 'X-OpenStack-Nova-API-Version', 'connection': 'close',
         'x-openstack-nova-api-version': '2.1',
         'date': 'Thu, 15 Oct 2015 05:24:39 GMT',
         'content-type': 'application/json'}
         Body:  _log_request_full /usr/local/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/tempest_lib/common/rest_client.py:414
 [..] End of API log [compute: Delete server]

Change-Id: I8a615da6f4a175dea08e0d239a5dc7d4538ef46d

Add temporary pin on jaraco.itertools

commit_message:
Add extra sanitize keys in mask_password

Currently we have a number of hard-coded lists of things to mask. It's
probably fine to leave those, but it would be nice to have an API to add
more entries to them so every consumer of the library doesn't have to
push their needed patterns into the library itself.

Closes-Bug: #1407811

Change-Id: Ic09843f9bcd287e54ce53d14a951d2bd09d9a1f0

commit_message:
Switch fuel-astute and fuel-nailgun-agent gates to use puppet templates

* Use existing puppet templates for fuel-astute and fuel-nailgun-agent
gate jobs instead of broken rake-dsvm template
* Enable only gate-{name}-puppet-unit-3.8-dsvm-centos7 jobs, since
different puppet versions don't matter for fuel-astute and
fuel-nailgun-agent
* Remove jenkins/jobs/ruby.yaml with broken rake-dsvm template

Change-Id: I44af35b8425c420cb1b2b158786fe9847f66fd30

https://github.com/pypa/pip/blob/develop/pip/req/req_file.py"}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2015-04-16 23:12:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

There's a few cosmetic things - look at the packaging.py in gerrit. No, six is not acceptable. Also the blank line with leading whitespace isn't needed, just remove it.

However, more importantly, depedendency_links is deprecated - pip doesn't read it, and will eventually remove support for it.

Our use of requirements.txt is idiosyncratic - we reflect it into install_requires, and as such, we need to error on such things rather than moving them over to dependency_links.

There's a fairly important refactoring discussion underway at the moment that is effectively about this as well, on openstack-dev. Until thats done I don't think we can make a solid decision about this patch, but my suggestion would be to make this thing that already errors (late, in setup), to error fast, at sdist time."}, {'account_id': 10786, 'date': '2015-11-19 08:53:29.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

[{'created': '2015-02-03 00:44:10.000000000', 'message': 'Add repository urls to dependency_links

Currently repository urls for non editables end up in the
`install_requires` list causing setup to fail.
In this commit, all usable external urls get inserted
into the `dependency_links` list with the corresponding
egg fragments parsed into package names and versions
(maintaining dashes if any) and added to `install_requires` list.

Change-Id: I4bdda9fd8ed12bb9e3f1d40fdf6340371e7df865
Closes-Bug: #1373623
'}]
commit_message:
Add repository urls to dependency_links

Currently repository urls for non editables end up in the
`install_requires` list causing setup to fail.
In this commit, all usable external urls get inserted
into the `dependency_links` list with the corresponding
egg fragments parsed into package names and versions
(maintaining dashes if any) and added to `install_requires` list.

Change-Id: I4bdda9fd8ed12bb9e3f1d40fdf6340371e7df865
Closes-Bug: #1373623

commit_message:
Remove IN-predicate warnings

The unit test logs currently contain 9 of the following warnings. Short
circuit and return an empty list in these cases rather than executing
the query needlessly.

    SAWarning: The IN-predicate on "<table>.<column>" was invoked with
an empty sequence. This results in a contradiction, which nonetheless
can be expensive to evaluate.  Consider alternative strategies for
improved performance.

Change-Id: I19460ed4e03a0db66186a4c231d315c2396b7eca

commit_message:
use common cache

we shouldn't need to different cache between update and create as
it will create a larger cache and more calls[1]. there is only one
instance of a resource and it's hash will be relevant regardless
of action.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/203109/7/ceilometer/dispatcher/gnocchi.py

Change-Id: I7b469335f4914436510166abb1e18f5958e5c966

commit_message:
Updates Swarm Heat Templates to Support Container Network Model

Previously, the Swarm templates did not support the Container
Network Model. The templates have been updated to support the
Flannel --network-driver. Conditionals have been added to support
future --network-drivers.

Partially-Implements: blueprint heat-network-refactor

Change-Id: Ie90e41568df05055b91764b861e08de6f689d864

apologies on bailing.

so this is exactly what my LRU comment in impl_sqlalchemy is about. if you look at SQL model, we have the exact same implementation, we have a hash of resource and if LRU was implemented it would cache the hash, and compare hash of imcoming resource to cache and decide whether to store or not.

the issue that arose when i looked at this a year ago was that we need another global storage layer to store caches (which only benefited sql at the time, mongo has no write issues). OR we have a local in memory LRU, this probably won't work because you'll have 100s of thousands of resources and the LRU size limit would probably be 1000's so there's a very good chance you're expiring your cache entries before you can even use them again. or you need to coordinate your collectors to ensure you always get a subset of resources.

there was also the issue where if you post to DB directly, it won't update the cache. so say collector receive a sample {resource: '1', metadata: {status:'on'}}. that cached hash now has {status:'on'}. if you POST for same resource, with {status:'off'}, it is updated in db, but your collector cache still says {status:'on'}... now if a sample comes in to collector with metadata:{status:'on'}, it should patch the resource, but it doesn't, because it's cache says it's already that.

those are the issues as i understand them, i may be wrong so please explain the above cases ^ :)

regarding Etags, i won't lie, i don't know what they are."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-17 21:46:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

Some responses to gordon. As a preface: Note that I'm not trying to say "zomg we must cache" but rather "what issues must we confront if we are going to cache". With that caveat, some responses:

* On cache size and lifetime: with dogpile you make the cache global and set an appropriate timeout. In the implementation here we're storing just an id/hash pair, which a) is tiny b) has its most meaningful lifetime surrounding one instance of a polling cycle. During that cycle there will bot lots of samples for any given resource, each will contain the same resource information, we only need to write it once. The cache will miss on the first check and hit on the rest. This corresponds with the behavior I've seen in real life testing. If the data then expire in the next 5 minutes, no big deal, we'll still cache the next cycle. If we make the expire time longer than we might also cache a update cycle.

  Or to put it another way, I really don't understand the issues you're stating when talking about LRU an coordination.

* On the "if you post to the DB directly" colliding with that cache, my answer/question to that would be "so what"? How much does it matter if we miss a patch. If it matters _that_ much that a) people shouldn't be messing with DB b) people should chill out and not let things matter so much.

* One critical thing that you may not be thinking about is that the metadata that gnocchi stores is _far_ more narrow than what was being stored in mongo or sql in ceilometer. Have a look at the attributes in: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/202500/9/etc/ceilometer/gnocchi_resources.yaml,cm or https://github.com/openstack/ceilometer/blob/master/ceilometer/dispatcher/resources/instance.py#L24

  Gnocchi doesn't care about all that flapping that can happen in arbitrary resource_metadata.

* ETags are cool, here's some really old background history that does a pretty good job of explaining how they can be relevant in this case: http://www.w3.org/1999/04/Editing/

> those are the issues as i understand them, i may be wrong so please explain the above cases ^ :)

I'm pretty sure I don't understand the cases you are trying to get explained, but I hope the above helped.'}, {'account_id': 8290, 'date': '2015-07-20 12:22:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Didn't carefully review and seems a profound change, (long commit message and long comments ;-D ), but can this change use oslo_cache ? [1], will learn and review in depth.

[1] http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/oslo.cache/"}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2015-07-20 12:50:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

i just pointing out that caching only benefited sql at the time which is why dogpile/global cache wasn't implemented. my original attempt was not backend specific.

regarding coordination the point was without it, each collector cache needs to scope to a size that can capture all resources, where if there's coordination, it'll only need to capture subset (x entries regardless of collectors, rather than x * number of collectors entries). that said, considering your lifecycle point, it may not be that bad.

for POSTs to db, i don't personally use that solution, but i know quite a few users who do (which is why i backed away from removing it). the importance of consistency is probably more important to them than to us.

for eTags, if i understand correctly, it still requires a query no? it's not checking something local."}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-07-20 13:12:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

liusheng: this is just a proof of concept patch to see whether we want to consider doing something like this at all. If it is turns out that we like the concept then I think the right way to implement would be to do a new patch, probably using oslo_cache to manage the caching.'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-07-20 13:21:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

gordon: gerrit sucks for having conversations but:

* In my model there is only one cache, shared between all collectors: no coordination required. And this is okay because a) cache is small-ish b) cache is short-lived c) cache is cheap. Or am I missing something?

The point I was trying to make by appending the comment about the kind of metadata that gnocchi actually stores is that the consistency risk goes _way_ down _and_ the usefulness of posting to the db as well because there's very very very little that's being stored that is worth changing. Further: with the way things work if you database gets out of sync with reality for this current polling/notificationcycle, it will be corrected in the next one. Won't it?

> the importance of consistency is probably more important to them than to us.

Sure but are the reasons/use-cases why people do make DB changes? Are they still present in a limited metadata world? And with gnocchi, there's less of that direct access to the database than ceilometer presents. Will it still be a problem.

I think we need to be crystal clear without ourselves and with the users that using gnocchi as a backend is _much_ different from how old-skool ceilometer worked. This didn't really come up in the mid-cycle, but probably should have:

    People who use gnocchi (as it currently exists) will no longer have a metadata store.

On Etags: there are still requests involved, but some of them can be avoided, especially if you maintain a etag cache of some kind. But the idea is that you can combine the kind of cache discussed in this patchset with effective use of etags to keep the number of requests down. None of it is perfect, just better."}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-11-05 16:47:38.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2015-11-05 16:49:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-07-17 16:09:51.000000000', 'message': "[WIP] Demonstrate dogpile cache of gnocchi resources

After discussion with sileht and gordc about the redundancy in
_create_resource there remained some confusion on how a cache might
be used to check to see if resources had already been written to the
gnocchi server.

This demonstrates one possible way. It's not been written to be
fully correct but rather to demonstrate the concept I was trying
(and failing) to explain in IRC.

What this does is store a key value pair in redis[1] where the key
is the resource id and the value is a the hash of the frozenset of
the attributes of the resource less the metrics[2]. When it is time
to create a resource we ask the cache:

  Are the resource attributes I'm about to store the same as the
  last ones stored for this id?

If the answer is yes we don't need to store the resource. That's all
it does and that is all it needs to do because if if the cache fails
to have the correct information that's the same as the cache not
existing in the first place.

To get this to work in the face of eventlet's eager beavering we
need to lock around create_resource so that we have a chance to
write the cache before another create_resource is called in this
process. Superficial investigation shows that this works out pretty
well because when, for example, you start a new instance the
collector will all of sudden try several  _create_resources, only
one of which actually needs to happen. The cache+lock makes sure
only that one happens when there is just one collector. Where there
are several collectors that won't be the case but _some_ of them
will be stopped. And that's the point here: better not perfect.

If this seem sensible we can consider doing it properly, which for
the most part means adding the necessary config options and cleaning
up the startup.

[1] Note that with redis is important to have a key_mangler
function if the redis server is being used for other purposes,
but that's not been included here.

[2] Metrics are not included because they are represented as
sub-dicts which are not hashable and thus cannot go in the
frozenset. Since the metrics are fairly static (coming from a yaml
file near you, soon) this shouldn't be a problem. If it is then we
can come up with a way to create a hash that can deal with
sub-dicts.

Change-Id: I1f2da145ca87712cd2ff5b8afecf1bca0ba53788

well because when, for example, you start a new instance the

only that one happens when there is just one collector. Where there
are several collectors that won't be the case but _some_ of them
will be stopped. And that's the point here: better not perfect.

"}, {'created': '2015-11-05 16:47:38.000000000', 'message': "[WIP] Demonstrate dogpile cache of gnocchi resources

After discussion with sileht and gordc about the redundancy in
_create_resource there remained some confusion on how a cache might
be used to check to see if resources had already been written to the
gnocchi server.

This demonstrates one possible way. It's not been written to be
fully correct but rather to demonstrate the concept I was trying
(and failing) to explain in IRC.

What this does is store a key value pair in redis[1] where the key
is the resource id and the value is a the hash of the frozenset of
the attributes of the resource less the metrics[2]. When it is time
to create a resource we ask the cache:

  Are the resource attributes I'm about to store the same as the
  last ones stored for this id?

If the answer is yes we don't need to store the resource. That's all
it does and that is all it needs to do because if if the cache fails
to have the correct information that's the same as the cache not
existing in the first place.

To get this to work in the face of eventlet's eager beavering we
need to lock around create_resource so that we have a chance to
write the cache before another create_resource is called in this
process. Superficial investigation shows that this works out pretty
well because when, for example, you start a new instance the
collector will all of sudden try several  _create_resources, only
one of which actually needs to happen. The cache+lock makes sure
only that one happens when there is just one collector. Where there
are several collectors that won't be the case but _some_ of them
will be stopped. And that's the point here: better not perfect.

If this seem sensible we can consider doing it properly, which for
the most part means adding the necessary config options and cleaning
up the startup.

This now also does the caching around _update_resource as well and
there it starts showing its true usefulness. Lots of cache hits.
The resulting code is now horribly un-DRY but that should be
fixable, especially with some of the other refactorings under
consideration for this chunk of code.

[1] Note that with redis is important to have a key_mangler
function if the redis server is being used for other purposes,
but that's not been included here.

[2] Metrics are not included because they are represented as
sub-dicts which are not hashable and thus cannot go in the
frozenset. Since the metrics are fairly static (coming from a yaml
file near you, soon) this shouldn't be a problem. If it is then we
can come up with a way to create a hash that can deal with
sub-dicts.

Change-Id: I1f2da145ca87712cd2ff5b8afecf1bca0ba53788
"}, {'created': '2015-11-06 14:09:27.000000000', 'message': "A dogpile cache of gnocchi resources

is the resource id and the value is a hash of the frozenset of
the attributes of the resource less the defined metrics[1]. When it

it does and that is all it needs to do because if the cache fails
to have the correct information that's the same as the cache not
existing in the first place.

To get this to work in the face of eventlet's eager beavering we
need to lock around create_resource and update_resource so that
we have a chance to write the cache before another *_resource is
called in this process. Superficial investigation shows that this
works out pretty well because when, for example, you start a new

_create_resources, only one of which actually needs to happen.
The lock makes sure only that one happens when there is just
one collector. Where there are several collectors that won't be
the case but _some_ of them will be stopped. And that's the point
here: better not perfect.

The cache is implemented using oslo_cache which can be configured
via oslo_config with an entry such as:

    [cache]
    backend = dogpile.cache.redis
    backend_argument = url:redis://localhost:6379
    backend_argument = db:0
    backend_argument = distributed_lock:True
    backend_argument = redis_expiration_time:600

The cache is exercised most for resource updates (as you might
expect) but does still sometimes get engaged for resource creates
(as described above).

A cache_key_mangler is used to ensure that keys generated by the
gnocchi dispatcher are in their own namespace.

commit_message:
A dogpile cache of gnocchi resources

What this does is store a key value pair in oslo_cache where the key
is the resource id and the value is a hash of the frozenset of
the attributes of the resource less the defined metrics[1]. When it
is time to create or update a resource we ask the cache:

  Are the resource attributes I'm about to store the same as the
  last ones stored for this id?

If the answer is yes we don't need to store the resource. That's all
it does and that is all it needs to do because if the cache fails
to have the correct information that's the same as the cache not
existing in the first place.

To get this to work in the face of eventlet's eager beavering we
need to lock around create_resource and update_resource so that
we have a chance to write the cache before another *_resource is
called in this process. Superficial investigation shows that this
works out pretty well because when, for example, you start a new
instance the collector will all of sudden try several
_create_resources, only one of which actually needs to happen.
The lock makes sure only that one happens when there is just
one collector. Where there are several collectors that won't be
the case but _some_ of them will be stopped. And that's the point
here: better not perfect.

The cache is implemented using oslo_cache which can be configured
via oslo_config with an entry such as:

    [cache]
    backend = dogpile.cache.redis
    backend_argument = url:redis://localhost:6379
    backend_argument = db:0
    backend_argument = distributed_lock:True
    backend_argument = redis_expiration_time:600

The cache is exercised most for resource updates (as you might
expect) but does still sometimes get engaged for resource creates
(as described above).

A cache_key_mangler is used to ensure that keys generated by the
gnocchi dispatcher are in their own namespace.

[1] Metrics are not included because they are represented as
sub-dicts which are not hashable and thus cannot go in the
frozenset. Since the metrics are fairly static (coming from a yaml
file near you, soon) this shouldn't be a problem. If it is then we
can come up with a way to create a hash that can deal with
sub-dicts.

Closes-Bug: #1483634
Change-Id: I1f2da145ca87712cd2ff5b8afecf1bca0ba53788

commit_message:
Read region from config and handle payload

The config file has 'region' under 'service' group but the code
was looking for it in the default section.
The payload instance doesn't have 'readable' method always.
Removing the condition check and test per review comments.

Change-Id: I8da70ebfa1ef73b7613ea6a179ad5cd4b31921ee

commit_message:
Address hacking check H405

Previously, there were a string of commits to keystone that addresed ignored
hacking checks. This commit does the same for H405 in keystoneauth. This
also modifies our tox.ini so that we no longer ignore H405 violations.

Change-Id: I0ac1165f309edd486639e2729c18330b1d062eb3
Closes-Bug: 1482773

This issue was actually caught by rally-ci (rally-pg-py27-unit) but was
ignored by revievers.

    .tox/py27/bin/python -m unittest discover tests/unit

commit_message:
Fix broken logic in some neutron scenarios

_get_or_create_network: create networks only if there is no networks
in context.

_get_or_create_subnets: create subnets only if there is no subnets
in context.

Unit tests are passing because of bug in ddt [0]
This issue was actually caught by rally-ci (rally-pg-py27-unit) but was
ignored by revievers.

Running tests without testr may be used as workaround:

    .tox/py27/bin/python -m unittest discover tests/unit

[0] https://github.com/txels/ddt/issues/35

Change-Id: Ib77bd4f7eeaec2ed3a712e1d56a20d1f87325264

commit_message:
Enhance test_alarms

Use specific alarm definition id in list alarms
instead of deleting all the alarm definitions after every single test.
Improved test_list_alarms_by_lifecycle_state and test_list_alarms_by_link

Change-Id: I3e7064b505922fff6cee4ee1854aeaa75fb08287

commit_message:
Make vagrant README.rst more accurate

the README.rst contains few errors in terms configuration file, number
of nodes. It also misses few pieces of critical information such as the
VM password, horizon login userid and password. This patch fixes these problems.

Change-Id: I64686db730a0434effded91cd47160cb1220d441
Closes-bug: #1517570

commit_message:
Fix H404/405 violations for service clients

There is a lot of H404/405 violations in Tempest now, and that leads
difficult to migrate the code to tempest-lib or the other projects'
repos. This patch fixes these violations for service clients.

Change-Id: Icf9f6fa4ea52a1fe72253391abf4880b1f8ed497

commit_message:
Merge tag '1.0.0'

This is a null-merge of the 1.0.0 release tag back into the master
branch so that the 1.0.0 tag will appear in the git commit history of
the master branch. It contains no actual changes to the master branch,
regardless of how our code review system's UI represents it. Please
ask in #openstack-infra if you have any questions, and otherwise try
to merge this as quickly as possible to avoid later conflicts on the
master branch.

Change-Id: I7b721084e8dfd900ccfafc136b2d91dd2c7475b3

commit_message:
Multinode job for live-migration

Basic enablement and clean-up of live-migration tests.
First attempt was to configure tempest in a hook, which
wasn't good idea, this patch actually fixes this. So d-g
make all configuration, and current hook only executes tests.

This is used in the gate-tempest-dsvm-multinode-live-migration job
which is run on the experimental queue only right now.

Change-Id: Ie28823fa1e8863b24391e503d04b031c421f0cd2

commit_message:
Fix H404/405 violations for tools

There is a lot of H404/405 violations in Tempest now, and that leads
difficult to migrate the code to tempest-lib or the other projects'
repos. This patch fixes these violations for tools for enabling
H404/405 rules on Tempest.

Change-Id: I4e1d78532d8f96edd5fd28a7bd2d62181fe9144b

commit_message:
Move endpoint_filter migrations into keystone core

This is the most basic way to move the endpoint_filter migrations into
the keystone core migrations path. Check to see if the migration was
performed already via the extension and if so skip performing it again.

DocImpact: Do not run the endpoint filter extension migrations, they are
now included in core and run by default.
Co-Authored-By: Jamie Lennox <jamielennox@redhat.com>
Partially implements: bp move-extensions

Change-Id: I51e711ed208dcc79531ac3a42b817063a2c712b8

commit_message:
Remove unnecessary functions in template_utils

These functions already been deprecated, and replaced by utils.
I see no point why we should keep them here. I suggest we just remove them.

Change-Id: I2116708e553e0ad30cd1d7b6bc1e43bfc4263c72

commit_message:
Make alarm groups configurable on overview page

This allows the alarm groups to be configured per tenant in the
horizon overview panel, similar to how the dashboard links are managed

Change-Id: I99be0af3a74c34342eecc9ae52a67a6d6d41a5d7

commit_message:
Move endpoint filter into keystone core

Remove endpoint_filter as an extension and move it to a core resource,
i.e. consolidate endpoint_filter extension into catalog.
For now we leave the database migrations in the extension directory,
this will address in a separate patch.

DocImpact: Remove the endpoint_filter extension from keystone's
paste pipeline.
Co-Authored-By: Jamie Lennox <jamielennox@redhat.com>
Partially implements: bp move-extensions

Change-Id: Ib8969d584f6be053aaad6e6051fde5e3b7ef7485

commit_message:
Require all fields on alarm definition PUT request

It seems unexpected to have some fields filled
with default values for a PUT request. Instead,
require all fields to be explicitly set for PUT

Change-Id: I570a89bcd8b4ac231283bdccdcf2645e6f3aa59b

commit_message:
Add ODL_BOOT_WAIT_URL to odl-releases/beryllium-snapshot-0.4.0

Thisl will make stacking of ODL that release a lot faster, since
it waits only as much as needed for ODL to become operational.

Change-Id: I9667251ce2192c4e5fa7861123e9d06bc1aea556

ConfigDrive creation fails on Python 3 when writing metadata to file
due to the fact that in Python 3 only bytes can be written to a file.

This patch fixes this issue by replacing jsonutils.dumps with
jsonutils.dump_as_bytes and thus ensuring that all data that is to

Closes-Bug: #1502583

commit_message:
Fixes Python 3 str issue in ConfigDrive creation

ConfigDrive creation fails on Python 3 when writing metadata to file
due to the fact that in Python 3 only bytes can be written to a file.

This patch fixes this issue by replacing jsonutils.dumps with
jsonutils.dump_as_bytes and thus ensuring that all data that is to
be written is bytes and not str.

Change-Id: Ie84f8badb185295fe019d80f8036aeb941709342
Closes-Bug: #1502583

commit_message:
Pin oslo.versionedobjects version

As oslo.versionedobjects include new fix
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/246721/
but it not release new version to include that fix
so jenkins still failed for that. We need pin to not
use version with that issue.

Change-Id: Ib589fb019f94a9f44925b378dccfadabdd9e5463

commit_message:
[Do not review]Test code for Bug1318528.

call_driver in neutron/agent/dhcp/agent.py will instantiate
driver class every time. This patch will create a driver
instance and use it for every action.

Change-Id: If1eea5367db9e27ab6003257045873acfb77c1c1
Partially-Bug: #1318528

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be

    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code

commit_message:
Move revoke sql migrations to common

This is the most basic way to move the revoke migrations into
the keystone core migrations path. Check to see if the migration was
performed already via the extension and if so skip performing it again.

Also had to delete tests in test_sql_livetest, since they were no
longer valid, they were testing the revocation extension behavior.

Also removed a few tests from test_sql_upgrade, they were also
testing extension behaviour logic and were creating the revoke tables
before the tests to create them in the common migration repo.

DocImpact: Do not run the revoke extension migrations, they are now
included in core and run by default

Change-Id: I8a1456bef2db3b11a364f34f38d1e6494f4b0e91
Implements: bp move-extensions

commit_message:
Move revoke extension into core

Remove revoke as an extension and move it to a core resource.
For now we leave the database migrations in the extension directory
until we have a general policy for merging these into core.

DocImpact: update keystone-paste and remove revoke from pipeline

Change-Id: I2d6f425a508b7acb4b4d079e4387f25bf7555683
Implements: bp move-extensions

commit_message:
Move oauth1 sql migrations to common

This is the most basic way to move the oauth1 migrations into
the keystone core migrations path. Check to see if the migration was
performed already via the extension and if so skip performing it again.

DocImpact: You should no longer run the migrations for the oauth extension

Change-Id: I8cea6748e7a5ae2b01320b4d6a9866e60ff2ea74

commit_message:
Move oauth1 extension into core

Remove oauth1 as an extension and move it to a core resource.
For now we leave the database migrations in the extension directory
until we have a general policy for merging these into core.

DocImpact: update keystone-paste and remove oauth1 from pipeline

Change-Id: I0ed1ec44d42c3b379a5c2a40e3e6298842dfc01d
Implements: bp move-extensions

commit_message:
Move federation sql migrations to common

This is the most basic way to move the federation migrations into
the keystone core migrations path. Check to see if the migration was
performed already via the extension and if so skip performing it again.

Change-Id: Id437bb68d281ee51e9a671591051c30c35f41bf0
Implements: bp move-extensions

while this change adds such property, a volume created and actually used with multiattach enabled can become unmanageable by Heat due to the fact, that volume resources rely on current "single-attach" behavior when:
- resizing an attached volume and attaching it back [1]
- checking that attachment/detachment is complete [2,3] (though I'm not sure what's the status of the Cinder volume and logic of this status transition would be when multi-attachment is allowed)
- ? might have missed something still.. 

We have to fix these places too to allow for real cinder multi-attach support in Heat

[1] https://github.com/openstack/heat/blob/master/heat/engine/resources/openstack/cinder/volume.py#L355
[2] https://github.com/openstack/heat/blob/master/heat/engine/clients/os/cinder.py#L150
[3] https://github.com/openstack/heat/blob/master/heat/engine/clients/os/cinder.py#L162'}, {'account_id': 8289, 'date': '2015-08-10 07:46:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Pavlo Shchelokovskyy:
Thanks for reviewing. Yes, you're right, there are some inappropriate codes in heat if nova implement the multiple attach, but for now only cinder support to create a volume which can set whether allow to multiattch. So I just to support the property for cinder volume."}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2015-08-14 09:20:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Support 'multiattach' for cinder volume

This patch only supports 'multiattach' property for
cinder volume resource.
We have to fix some places too to allow for real
multi-attach support in Heat after nova support this
feature.

Change-Id: I8d89d8eb8338f614638049d7da4a680a4b0846f7
Closes-Bug: #1468981

commit_message:
Move federation extension into keystone core

Remove federation as an extension and move it to a core resource.
For now we leave the database migrations in the extension directory
until we have a general policy for merging these into core.

Some instances of federation constants were removed because
they were causing a circular dependency, these can be refactored in
a later patch.

DocImpact: You should no longer run the migrations for this extension
Implements: bp move-extensions

Co-Authored-By: Nithya Renganathan <narengan@us.ibm.com>

Change-Id: If5857a6ee4c7c527929069b25beab40f4c5d87e2

commit_message:
docs: re-organise the API concept docs

This moves material from 2.0_general_info into the index to make an
improved index page.

Some details from the general_info have been moved into the server
concepts, where that information is a better fit.

The general_info page has been expanded with TODOs so we are clear
about some the missing details.

Co-Authored-By: Ed Leafe <ed@leafe.com>

Change-Id: I2a878586d6a073026d1f997e6f0f7ee87a01f726

commit_message:
Fix notification driver package

In oslo.messaging change:
Ifb96c2ae9868426cac2700bf4917c27c02c90b15

the private package for the messaging driver was changed
to a public package. So we should fix our reference here
in our setup.cfg

Closes-Bug: #1513630

Change-Id: I6b066f4f1b6c6485cb67ca5f8a2a17359521c264

This works but I still want to understand how Instance comes back as 2.0 when it was requested as 1.23. I didn't think it's a race with mocks because I find objects.Instance == objects.InstanceV1 before the call"}, {'account_id': 4690, 'date': '2015-11-18 01:31:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

To close the loop on what I was trying to understand:

In o.vo 0.12.0 the fake indirection api object_class_action('1.23') was called so even though the manifest lookup in the fake had '2.0', the target_version for obj_to_primitive was '1.23' from the objver param so a InstanceV1 was returned.

In o.vo 0.13.0, the remotable_classmethod decorator (inside o.vo) pulls the manifest and calls object_class_action_versions with it, so the only possible instance to get back from that is InstanceV2. The objver is not a parameter in object_class_action_versions, only the manifest. The content of the manifest is consistent between running the cells unit tests with o.vo 0.12.0 and 0.13.0."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2015-11-18 02:59:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

commit_message:
Fix Nova's indirection fixture override

This mirrors the indirection fixture override that we have for
object_class_action() while we transition fully to the base
VersionedObjectRegistry. This prevents us from breaking with current
oslo.versionedobjects.

This also caused a few other tests to get run with manifest calls,
which needed to be converted to continue to work. Also, because
liberty still has both InstanceV1 and InstanceV2, this tickled another
case where we need to use the instance base class for a mox.IsA() check.

Change-Id: I2aaa42784b2cc5c6898a3fac0c951dd57dd4f4c6
Closes-Bug: #1516805
(cherry picked from commit 1b3fbfb087998633ea66db223c0f7c201f69e49a)

commit_message:
Add Fernet FAQ

We've been getting various questions on Fernet tokens for a while. We should
add some of the common ones to docs.

Change-Id: I8dd42ef1657cf6312636f1f59a5897b6956a4ee4

commit_message:
Update error message to a uniform format

Update error messages so they follow the same format.
Also, add i18n where it is missing, fix typo and grammatical
errors in messages, and fix vague messages so they are more
clear.

Change-Id: I06d29b4d8448f8c08fa199a316942f373b968d22

commit_message:
Log to sys.stderr to avoid "No handlers could be found..."

On occasion, logging can occur before logging is ready, resulting
in unseen warnings/errors, for instance in oslo_config. To avoid
this, we temporarily log to sys.stderr until things are ready.

Change-Id: I9a3ce94881d1cdaddfe5a616dca0bdbf5326eddc
Closes-Bug: 1516128

Hi Eric,

I see what you are saying.  If the user uses the maintenance flag during volume migration, no other operations such as attach will be allowed, so it will be safe.

If the user didn't use the maintenance flag during volume migration, and someone attempts an attach, migration is supposed to be canceled and things will be messed up and need to be cleaned up.  I believe Vincent has been working on cleanups if another operation comes in and cancels volume migration.  I'm not sure what the status is with that effort.  I think the cleanup should be taken care of by the manager or some layer higher than the driver.  I searched other drivers that have implemented update_migrated_volume, but doesn't seem that they are doing anything special.  If you think I could make any changes in this driver to make it safer, I'll be happy to change it!

Vincent, what is the status of the cleanup patch?

Thanks!"}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2015-11-18 16:46:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

commit_message:
ScaleIO driver: update_migrated_volume

This patch implements the update_migrated_volume function.
Without this change, when the migrate finishes, the original
volume will be deleted but the name on the new volume will not
be changed to the old id even though the Cinder database will
be updated. The volume name is a base64() encoding of the Cinder
volume id so any calls after the migrate fail since the lookup
fails.

Also changed 'SCALEIO' to connector.SCALEIO now that os-brick 0.4.0
is released.

Closes-Bug: #1512387
Change-Id: I70fe4bd651b0ac87b9208efb5918a4cdaf6f06b4

commit_message:
Fix up issues after decomposition

The removal of the ODL code from the neutron core tree caused some
unit tests to break, which are fixed by this patch.

Import ml2_odl options in opendaylight mechanism driver

In addition, other opendaylight drivers' way
of imporing ml2_odl options is updated too.

Co-Authored-By: Henry Gessau <gessau@cisco.com>
Co-Authored-By: gong yong sheng <gong.yongsheng@99cloud.net>

Closes-Bug: #1514823
Closes-Bug: #1516966

Change-Id: Iae9cc53c6cd926339e59db1ffc136a6b106cde5a

commit_message:
Reduce vdu2 flavor from  ml.medium to ml.tiny

Some dsvm nodes may has little memory which cannot provide enough
for multiple VDU tests. This patch reduces the vdu2's flavor into
ml.tiny.

Change-Id: Ia7ddc7656d4909e0e977915f70a97baedb782ed9
Closes-bug: 1516204

commit_message:
Add support for Neutron L3 HA feature

Neutron L3 HA feature adds an ability to schedule a virtual router to at least
two L3 agents and an opportunity to establish connection faster after L3 agent
failover than router rescheduling.
L3 HA is currently not compatible with Neutron DVR

Change-Id: If62bc89c493241b78422e55f1865031db23705ed
Blueprint: neutron-vrrp-deployment

commit_message:
Rename ClusterUpgradeHandler

Name ClusterUpgradeHandler should be used for handling uri
/cluster/<id>/upgrade.

Current handler performs clone of environment for upgrading. Thus, rename
ClusterUpgradeHandler to ClusterUpgradeCloneHandler.

Blueprint: upgrade-major-openstack-environment
Change-Id: I6c98e0882c300d587caa32429b49b22baa9ad82f

@YAMAMOTO Takashi
for my usecase the mechanism driver is currently needed to support co existence of VHOST_USER  enabled node with kernel vhost nodes in the same cloud.

the VHOST_USER vif type which is only supported with dpdk netdev datapath has several deployment time requirements which must be satisfied for it to work.

first ovs must be compiled with dpdk 2.0.

second dpdk must be compile with vhost-user support enabled(default).

third ovs must be run with the --dpdk parameter
and finally the datapath type of the bridge must be netdev.

if any of these 4 condition are not met ovs will not support vhost-user. these are just the ovs related deployment actions there are more that must be taken to correctly configure openstack and then platform for vhost-user (allocating hugepages,installing correct libvirt and qemu versions, configuring hugepage backed flavours and assigning flavours to host aggregates...). 

when we introduces vhost-user in the kilo release we provided a forked copy of ovs l2 agent with just these two changes. From the reasons above the choice of vhost-user support is firmly a deployment decision which is why we had our own agent type and mech driver. For liberty we would like eliminate this forked agent and use the standard ovs agent. we still want to maintain the agent type for now but there is no reason to have a separate forked code base.

in mitika i hope upstream modifications to the standard ovs mechanism driver to enable it to support vhost-user however i would like to wait for the two nova changes below  to be completed before starting that work as to convert this from a deployment to a runtime decision requires more information then currently available.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/190917/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/193668/

in general allowing the standard agent to be reused by other mechanism drivers allows it to support more deployment configurations. when adding new guest interface you generally do not need to modify the flows created by the agent.'}, {'account_id': 11604, 'date': '2015-08-18 15:24:16.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 10.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-18 16:54:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: Verified+1

After discussing with Kevin, it appears the plan is to try and let this merge into Liberty. It would then allow the vhost-user folks to not need a forked agent. However, we'd be deprecating this immediately in Liberty, and removing it in Mitaka once the actual agent changes merge. To me, I'm not in favor of this because it feels really wonky and like a hack. But I'm curious what others think. If I'm the only one against this and the patch is mergeable, then maybe we merge it and do the wonky deprecation hack."}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-09-22 19:39:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13: Code-Review+2

Current context for reviewers (Sean, correct me if I'm wrong):

Currently there has to be an entirely separate mechanism driver and agent that reports back a different type to the Neutron server in order to send Nova different binding params for VMs to use things like OVS dpdk.

The correct fix for this is to have the L2 agent report back the supported VIF parameters by its OVS setup to the Neutron server via report_state. The OVS mech driver would then choose the correct binding information to send back to Nova whenever a port is bound on this host.

However, this will require larger changes on the agent side to extract this information from OVS and will require refactoring on the mech driver side to make the Nova binding details conditional based on the configuration of the agent. It's much too late in the cycle for that big of a change.

This patch eliminates the need for operators to run different versions of the L2 agent so they get consistent bug fixes and behavior during upgrades. They just set the name of the agent via this config to something one of the different mech drivers is expecting on the server side. Since the correct refactor will happen in M, we are immediately deprecating this workaround.

Even though this is a hack, I think the value of getting operators all running the same agent code is worth it rather than having to manage a bunch of tweaked forks for different Nova VIF params."}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-09-22 19:46:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13: Code-Review+2

Kevin has convinced me. I've added the bug to liberty-rc1."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-22 20:43:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13: Verified-1

commit_message:
Adds configurable agent type

This change introduces a new agent_type config option which
allows the ovs agent to be reused by out of tree
mechanism drivers.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I48f4be4b1d51bcff62e86e5814c12bd9bfa3c902
Closes-Bug: #1469871

commit_message:
add "unreleased" release notes page

We need a release notes page to show notes for unreleased versions by
scanning the "current" branch. This ensures that notes files cannot be
merged if they break the releasenotes job.

Change-Id: Ie1277428a3053d183df73bac882adc8aa0ac1079
(cherry picked from commit 1f91392267f7377bd01ee524396cfbe4127b83d8)

commit_message:
Fix the wrong reference for DeprecationWarning

warnings module not have such attribute, so we need use built-in
exceptions https://docs.python.org/2/library/warnings.html

Change-Id: I41e0c5ecfecc6e30855c722dd4c4f3fe68fbcf27
Closes-Bug: #1517280

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-18 16:08:49.000000000', 'message': "enable ebtables workaround in devstack

One of the biggest bugs in the gate right now is racing with libvirt
on ebtables for guests. This is because ebtables and the interfaces on
the kernel are not multi process safe. If you run ebtables twice
simultaneously it can bounce off the kernel or even possibly corrupt
the ebtables state.

This was addressed by adding a --concurrent flag in ebtables, however
every program calling ebtables must opt into using that flag. And if
anyone doesn't, the race remains. Nova is getting this support now,
libvirt gained it in 1.2.11, after metacloud discovered this
issue. However libvirt 1.2.11 is newer than we have in the gate.

We have an alternative workaround in devstack which replaces
/sbin/ebtables with a shell script that flocks and calls the real
ebtables behind the scene. This will work to stop bleeding out on this
bug and creating recheck madness.

Because this moves a file in /sbin, it's an opt in flag. As after a
package upgrade on a devstack it will be undone. However for the
single use case in devstack-gate it's fine, and should massively

commit_message:
enable ebtables workaround in devstack

One of the biggest bugs in the gate right now is racing with libvirt
on ebtables for guests. This is because ebtables and the interfaces on
the kernel are not multi process safe. If you run ebtables twice
simultaneously it can bounce off the kernel or even possibly corrupt
the ebtables state.

This was addressed by adding a --concurrent flag in ebtables, however
every program calling ebtables must opt into using that flag. And if
anyone doesn't, the race remains. Nova is getting this support now,
libvirt gained it in 1.2.11, after metacloud discovered this
issue. However libvirt 1.2.11 is newer than we have in the gate.

We have an alternative workaround in devstack which replaces
/sbin/ebtables with a shell script that flocks and calls the real
ebtables behind the scene. This will work to stop bleeding out on this
bug and creating recheck madness.

Because this moves a file in /sbin, it's an opt in flag. As after a
package upgrade on a devstack it will be undone. However for the
single use case in devstack-gate it's fine, and should massively
decrease the race failures we find in the gate.

Depends-On: Ic6fa847eba34c21593b9df86a1c2c179534d0ba5

Change-Id: Ib48fc921c282ec7dad4a9e18460f2a064faae182
Related-Bug: #1501558

commit_message:
Add "unreleased" release notes page

We need a release notes page to show notes for unreleased versions by
scanning the "current" branch. This ensures that notes files cannot be
merged if they break the releasenotes job.

Change-Id: Id9e9d62b8b87068f940c0beee8ce37f32ab48266
(cherry picked from commit 4c2dfa538a6561a21a472c9ce41159c733ea6f09)

commit_message:
install ebtables locking workaround

ebtables is racing with itself when nova and libvirt attempt to create
rules at the same time in the nat table. ebtables now has an explicit
--concurrent flag, that all tools must opt into to prevent ebtables
from inherently being unsafe to run.

libvirt gained this support in 1.2.11, which is too new for our ubuntu
primary testing environment. Nova still hasn't added this support,
though even if it did, we'd run into the issue with libvirt.

We can do the most ghetto thing possible and create a wrapper for
ebtables that does explicit locking on it's own. It's pretty terrible,
but it should work. And it is the kind of work around that people
unable to upgrade libvirt will probably need to do.

This is an opt in value which we should set in the gate to True.

Related-Bug: #1501558

I'm sorry but a client side fix feels like a cheap hack here. I'm very opposed to add magic sleeps anywhere to work around issues like this. Just doing this to tempest's clients doesn't prevent anyone from hitting this issue when using any other client.

It would be marginally better if this fix were applied in tests that were expecting this to fail but it doesn't, but I'm pretty sure I'd be -1 on that too."}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2015-10-12 21:50:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Matthew, I completely agree with your distaste (and yes, the implication is that all clients must assume the same behavior), but I don't think we have a better solution. The only viable alternative is to sleep on the service side, which I also have proposed (although this fails keystone's test suite, because the test suite is slowed down so much that it times out).

Looking outside OpenStack for another solution might include proposing to github.com/fernet/spec that we add microsecond-level timestamps and version bump the entire specification, but we'd technically still have this same race condition, just within one-microsecond instead of within one second. If we pursue that, then I would see this patch as a viable temporary solution until we can consume a new version of Fernet (at which point, we could relax or remove the sleep here)."}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2015-10-12 22:55:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Matthew: I reported this issue upstream as well, https://github.com/fernet/spec/issues/12'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-12 23:33:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

We should also keep in mind that a fix to Fernet to add sub-second precision still won't be the silver bullet. Consider the following case. If you get a token at .01 or a new second. Given that the token creation time is now persisted in the Fernet token format, and the expiration time we have control over in the keystone payloads. Both will have sub-second precision, microsecond precision specifically. Let's say you change your password at .05 seconds, which will be stored as a revocation event in the database as .000000 because the SQL backend doesn't support sub-second precision datetime formats. Now, we should expect that validating the original token should return 404, which is a case we have in tempest [0]. The original token will actually returns as 200 OK because the issued at time (.01) happens *after* the issued before time of the revocation event (.000000 - because of truncation due to sql).

We don't hit this with the uuid case because the token is actually removed from the database. The uuid token provider doesn't have a hard requirement on the revocation API, because they are persistent.


[0] https://github.com/openstack/tempest/blob/f207b353b7da5d9e9cd282a3e8e953995674092d/tempest/api/identity/v3/test_users.py#L63-L66"}, {'account_id': 5046, 'date': '2015-10-13 21:55:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I think dealing with the sub-second precision in MySQL's datetime type will be a much more intricate fix and will take some detailed planning, no doubt."}, {'account_id': 7350, 'date': '2015-10-14 10:44:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 5046, 'date': '2015-11-03 15:52:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

This patch makes it so that there is a one second wait when changing a password
with Keystone. This is done because when we lose sub-second precision with
Fernet tokens there is the possibility of a token being issued and revoked
within the same second. Keystone will err on the side of security and return a
404 NotFound when validating a token that was issued in the same second as a
revocation event.

For example, it is possible for a revocation event to happen at .000001, but it
will be stored in MySQL as .00000 because of sub-second truncation. A token can
be created at .000002, but the creation time of that token, according to
Fernet, will be .000000, because Fernet tokens don't have sub-second precision.
When that token is validated, it will appear invalid even though it was created
*after* the revocation event.

commit_message:
Fix race condition when changing passwords

This patch makes it so that there is a one second wait when changing a password
with Keystone. This is done because when we lose sub-second precision with
Fernet tokens there is the possibility of a token being issued and revoked
within the same second. Keystone will err on the side of security and return a
404 NotFound when validating a token that was issued in the same second as a
revocation event.

For example, it is possible for a revocation event to happen at .000001, but it
will be stored in MySQL as .000000 because of sub-second truncation. A token can
be created at .000002, but the creation time of that token, according to
Fernet, will be .000000, because Fernet tokens don't have sub-second precision.
When that token is validated, it will appear invalid even though it was created
*after* the revocation event.

Change-Id: Ied83448de8af1b0da9afdfe6ce9431438215bfe0
Closes-Bug: 1473567

commit_message:
Add ip addr flush on ifdown to ensure IP addresses are removed.

This adds an ip add flush <interface> on ifdown to ensure that the IP
addresses are removed from the device even if something in the system
isn't working properly.  Specifically if you have disabled NetowrkManager
ifdown will sometimes not remove the IP.

Change-Id: I5050dd1045c557e8bb1c92c6267fd7fa163806a9
Signed-off-by: Ian Main <imain@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Enable conversion of the tree nodes into a digraph

Just like it's useful to be able to translate a execution
graph into a dot diagram, the same usefulness can be helpful
for the engine scoping hierarchy that is created, to make
it easily possible to do this provide a tree method that
converts itself (and its children) into a direct graph which
can then easily be exported as a dot diagram (and then
rendered as needed).

Change-Id: I0addc2dee4cdce03ee5f33832a419303abc77db4

commit_message:
Adding backup-reset-state to CLI

This patch adds the ability to reset the state of
a backup with the command backup-reset-state.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I5851bb21c62252f61ad6a09f01859582e774a9db
Closes-Bug: #1279764

commit_message:
Ensure file basepath exists

On a manual gnocchi install, i run into OSError on
/var/lib/gnocchi/measure. This is because the basepath
doesnt exist yet. On devstack this is handled. But we should
handle it if gnocchi is installed manually.

Change-Id: Iabe00a7cadede851ea3147d98bc2eba0708f92c3

commit_message:
Add service records for nova-api services

This adds service records for the API services for the purpose of
version-tracking. Unlike other services, these records are not periodically
updated, so this adds no additional runtime database burden. The API
services update the version (if necessary) of their record at startup.

This also adds filtering in three places to prevent us from exposing
API service records out of the hosts and availability-zone APIs.

Related to blueprint service-version-behavior
Change-Id: I66becb14788de42bee35064d1155dd919059bcb7

commit_message:
Reuse method to convert key to passphrase

This change removes duplicate code in the LuksEncryptor that converts
a raw key to a passphrase. The super class CryptsetupEncryptor already
defines a method for the conversion so it is used instead.

Change-Id: I9b0c347879d9a10652bcdfe84e9557e4e8246edd
