revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-17 23:08:47.000000000', 'message': 'Fix stack lock ActionInProgress in the admin case

When the engine starts and tries to reset the status of stacks in
progress, it tries to acquire the stack lock on them. The stack lock
queries the database to retrieve the name of the stack, but does a
tenant-scope query, thus fails when as we use the admin context during
startup. This fixes it by passing tenant_safe=False.

Change-Id: I4393fdb601eedb36d7288afd57fb5a1c96af7216
Closes-Bug: #1516712
(cherry picked from commit 9924d780e82d8419783177094d63c8333482a129)
'}]
commit_message:
Fix stack lock ActionInProgress in the admin case

When the engine starts and tries to reset the status of stacks in
progress, it tries to acquire the stack lock on them. The stack lock
queries the database to retrieve the name of the stack, but does a
tenant-scope query, thus fails when as we use the admin context during
startup. This fixes it by passing tenant_safe=False.

Change-Id: I4393fdb601eedb36d7288afd57fb5a1c96af7216
Closes-Bug: #1516712
(cherry picked from commit 9924d780e82d8419783177094d63c8333482a129)

Showing results, not sure what recommendations there are or how 512MB was decided. 

Looking at a pmap of the nova-compute process. This host is idle, with no special bits enabled like sriov on my interfaces. 
https://gist.github.com/jtaleric/addd9079d6cdf4f7cf42'}, {'account_id': 14985, 'date': '2015-11-18 21:51:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Because this is the default value for the nova service itself we should not be adjusting this. Techincally this should be updated to use $::os_service_default so the puppet module isn't providing any default and using the service's default value. It would better to push for nova to adjust this value themselves and switch this to $::os_service_default so that would be honored.  Alternatively set it in your composition layer."}, {'account_id': 10061, 'date': '2015-11-18 22:20:10.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

moving elsewhere.'}]

commit_message:
Changing the default reserved_host_memory_mb to be realistic.

A idle compute node consumes close to 1024MB of memory.

Bug: https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1282644
Change-Id: I6fe775e13a967a7272c2bf9d11759896ba1bd8ab

commit_message:
Configure corosync cluster-recheck-interval

Add the cluster_recheck_interval param with
a 190 sec default, configurable via hiera.
Add rspec and noop tests.

Closes-bug: #1517388

Change-Id: I82b7220e24282d1fbda69ed7d3788e2bdc0afcfc
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

only use unicodecsv for python 2.x

Only use unicodecsv for python 2, since the python 3 module works fine
with unicode data.

[{'created': '2015-11-18 21:17:59.000000000', 'message': "Support period in project names for branch override flag

Currently for oslo.config we end up looking for a environment variable:
OVERRIDE_OSLOCONFIG_PROJECT_BRANCH

We should convert the '.' in 'oslo.config' to an underscore ('_')

Change-Id: Ia650971b7adbf117a787acc3d64ff862e29d47ab
"}]
commit_message:
Support period in project names for branch override flag

Currently for oslo.config we end up looking for a environment variable:
OVERRIDE_OSLOCONFIG_PROJECT_BRANCH

We should convert the '.' in 'oslo.config' to an underscore ('_')

Change-Id: Ia650971b7adbf117a787acc3d64ff862e29d47ab

So the 'demo' user in 'demo' project is logged out when he tries to display his own project.

If we look at https://github.com/openstack/horizon/blob/2015.1.0/openstack_dashboard/api/keystone.py#L247 we see that admin is set to True, which leads to logging out. Spent some more time thinking about the scenario..

So what's happening is the user is show the list of their projects from: https://github.com/openstack/horizon/blob/master/openstack_dashboard/dashboards/identity/projects/views.py#L96

The project table always display a link regardless if the user have privilege or not.

I think what we can do is don't make the name render as link if the user doesn't have privilege for it, this would be a better UX.

We can achieve that by adding a flag for the tenants: https://github.com/openstack/horizon/blob/master/openstack_dashboard/dashboards/identity/projects/views.py#L96

to denote that this is user's project. And then in the tables.py use that flag to determine if the name should be render as link or text."}, {'account_id': 6650, 'date': '2015-11-10 22:59:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

is this better?  http://paste.openstack.org/show/478491/'}, {'account_id': 13325, 'date': '2015-11-11 16:00:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Lin Hua Cheng, maybe it is a very stupid question, but why do we need to show inactive project name if user has no rights to access it? Why we cannot just hide it?'}, {'account_id': 6650, 'date': '2015-11-12 00:02:41.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 1941, 'date': '2015-11-12 00:14:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

the code looks good to me. 

We just need to change the commit message, because the patch is now very different from what described in the commit msg :)'}, {'account_id': 1941, 'date': '2015-11-12 00:18:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Paul Karikh: There was a change in behavior that happened at some point on the project table.

The behavior for the projects table is list:
1. try to get all project
2. if the user doesn't have the authorization, just list all the projects the user have access to.

I think the reason this was made is to allow the user have a page to see all the project they can scope to, plus the ID.

I am not really sold though that #2 provides that much value, since the users can still see the list of projects they can scope to from the "Project" dropdown. But it is already there, to provide a better UX we should not render  the project ID as link if the user don't have access to it.

Hope that helps.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-12 00:57:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified+1

Some notes on this patch:

- Using keystone v2 -
If I'm an admin on the currently scoped project, all project names show as links regardless of whether I'm an admin or member.  That's fine for Horizon, as the default v2 policy file will still let me show project details for a project I'm only a member on, as long as my current token says I'm an admin on some other project.

- Using keystone v3 -
Whether to show the links is the same as above.  This causes problems because the v3 sample policy file checks for whether I'm an admin on the project I'm trying to show details for.  So Horizon shows links for things I don't have access to.

https://github.com/openstack/keystone/blob/master/etc/policy.v3cloudsample.json#L38

I don't think we need to hold this patch up for the v3 concerns, but we should think about disabling the links altogether for v3, since the token scope matters more."}, {'account_id': 17172, 'date': '2015-11-13 02:57:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Add policy check for project detail link

This change does a policy check for each row, to determine if
the link should be displayed or not.

Change-Id: Ia07c88216cdeb81c87da5c813bafb85e43c58e14
Closes-Bug: #1494548
Closes-Bug: #1418246

but Ceilometerclient supports it only since 2.0.0.

commit_message:
Bump ceilometerclient to 2.0.0

Ceilometer want to use keystoneauth session for each clients,
but Ceilometerclient supports it only since 2.0.0.

This change dumps ceilometerclient to 2.0.0

Change-Id: Ic7bbf9c98eb3f5a5d31da6f313458c4c4d62f59f

commit_message:
Add provider information to Create LoadBalancer

The API Reference guide does not mention the provider option
which exists in Load Balancer creation in LBaaS V2.
The following patch attempts to fix the same.

Change-Id: Iab5d65498ee0243771f8e4374cb8edf9b6a71cc6
Closes-Bug: #1516904

commit_message:
Make Neutron create_flavor_service_profile return dict

A flavor framework routine was returning a list instead of the
expected dictionary from a create call.  This caused problems
with an internal server error in _exclude_attributes_by_policy:
File "/opt/stack/neutron/neutron/api/v2/base.py", line 143,
in _exclude_attributes_by_policy:
for attr_name in data.keys():
AttributeError: 'list' object has no attribute 'keys'

Solution is to return dictionary that includes the desired
list of service ids.

Added unit test case.

Change-Id: If5adb75c23b4ae103bcdfbd34baf73f5108ad25b
Closes-Bug: 1486136

commit_message:
Release of python-glanceclient 1.2.0

1f1934e Add versions list function
bff356e Added reactivate/deactivate image using CLI
dfcb468 Fix the missing help descripiton of "image-create"
8a4cd79 Add documentation for running the functional tests
c7c0754 Updated from global requirements
d6a10f2 Remove unused sphinx Makefile
5a24705 Update docs to recommend KSA instead of KSC
84538d8 Use clouds.yaml from devstack for functional tests
4fb3092 Add translation to v2 shell
6b9133c Import i18n functions directly
8cf2bfc Updated from global requirements
b51634a improve readme contents
ca050ed Add support for setting Accept-Language header
3bd28bf Updated from global requirements
36937bb Use the subcomand parsed args instead of the base
afd1810 Stop trying to send image_size to the server
bf02b04 Support image deletion in batches in v2
a8a7c68 print usage when no argument is specified for python3
77012ee Updated from global requirements
603697a Updated from global requirements
df0f664 Do not use openstack.common.i18n in glance client
abf0381 Added unit tests for 'Unicode support shell client'
1f2fefb Use common identity parameters fro keystone client
c31c136 No auth when token and endpoint are passed
557acb1 Use dictionary literal for dictionary creation
c6addc7 Replace exception_to_str with oslo.utils function
586d401 Change ignore-errors to ignore_errors
05cd0c7 Add period in help message
b8a881f Don't get the image before deleting it
3d3d829 Fix human readable when size is None
19480df Add parsing the endpoint URL
22ce845 Fix Typos in comments
b9eee5e Add check Identity validate when get schemas

Change-Id: I2bba4fcdb7432a939397c0b50615bd27bf48f0cd

[Sahara] Add Swift to output data sources

Added support of Swift in Sahara Data Sources. The context does not
verify the output of the job. The cleanup deletes the output container.

commit_message:
Release python-glanceclient stable/kilo 0.17.3

01a6d7f Release Notes for 0.17.3
ffd135c Updated from global requirements
fab2ace Updated from global requirements
68cf63d Don't get the image before deleting it
15fe21d Updated from global requirements
e7a801d Ship the default image schema in the client
320bc6f V2: Do not validate image schema when listing
0acf7cc Expose 'is_base' schema property attribute

Change-Id: Ie4f60aa5ea11b154c19b65104de18716b6241fce

commit_message:
Create partition at max msdos limit for disks > 2TB

Currently there is a problem on partition creation for MBR
case. If disk exceeds 2TB, partition creation fails because
we are hitting max msdos limit. Detect total disk size, and if
it exceeds that limit, create the partition at the end of legal
limits.

Fixes-Bug: #1517077
Change-Id: I11dd3f11eaa6af764151b442768d10289ced6d3f

commit_message:
Bump oslo.utils to 2.8.0

Keystone needs to rely bug fix c5d9e6cde8d5f7ab2915996bcd54347a9fa521f9
on in 2.8.0, so bump the lower bound.

commit_message:
Add a better description for notification_driver

Improve description for the notification_driver
property in neutron.conf, so users will understand
how to configure it correctly.

Change-Id: Ib5d4c4b6eea5cabf58708d8201f9ff9c883b6c97

commit_message:
Disable IPv6 on bridge devices in LinuxBridgeManager

We don't want to create a bridge device with an IPv6 address because
it will see the Router Advertisement from Neutron.

Change-Id: If59a823804d3477c5d8877f46fcc4c018af57a5a
Closes-bug: 1302080

commit_message:
Fix inaccurate debug mode response

When running in debug mode, the server would put some text about
disabling debug mode to suppress details even when disabling debug
mode wouldn't make any difference in the response.

The fix is to:

1) In the base SecurityError class, check if the message is being
   overridden and only add the message about supressing details if
   the message is overridden.
2) Have only a single way to overriding the message and use that in
   UnexpectedError.

Change-Id: Ia924eb633deeaf1c80ee0d0e72d082d6a9e380a8
Closes-Bug: 1496530

Adding networking MidoNet element

This element provides all the packages and the puppet midonet module to
configure MidoNet in an OpenStack deployment.

checking for membership.

This also updates the task_manager code to look for more types

commit_message:
Add user group assignment API

Add methods for adding and removing users to/from groups and
checking for membership.

This also updates the task_manager code to look for more types
that we don't want to munchify because one of the new keystone
API methods being called returned a bool value.

This replaces Ida3cff3acdc1406c5e6d61500766a292565191fc

Change-Id: Ib34c116010312ed26b042621fcf2e7b5b774424f

commit_message:
Port share type extensions to core API

Changes:
- Register share type APIs as core API.
- Remove extensions code for share types.
- Leave rename of API 'post' data for future update which
  will be done with bump of microversion
  after port of all extensions to core API.

Partially implements bp ext-to-core

Change-Id: I334cc0fa8e69c2f9b5226f247149a0b9b748dd60

commit_message:
Port admin actions extension to core API

Changes:
- Register admin actions API as core API.
- Remove extension code for admin actions.
- Leave rename of admin actions API 'post' data for future update which
  will be done with bump of microversion
  after port of all extensions to core API.

Partially implements bp ext-to-core
Closes-Bug: #1510620

Change-Id: Ic8804cff5fa46003d2991372c6eb2a854b886dec

commit_message:
Last sync from oslo-incubator

oslo-incubator will cease to host common code soon. This is
hopefully the very last sync from oslo-incubator.

Changes:

7f37bf8 Correct a typo
f4b09ce Sort keys in table output in print_dict
0753799 Allow specifying a table header for the value column in...

Change-Id: I7eb71518e3c9c0c51b08188fa83298dd9eac93dc

commit_message:
Add Metrics Service

This is the first step toward centralizing the operations on passes,
failures, skips and fail rate (currently being done in multiple places)
into a single specialized service, to avoid repetition.

Change-Id: Ia346133a17ad0cff73c2410f1844e746888855cb

commit_message:
Remove inaccurate OSI Model reference

Updates to remove calling packets equal to frames. The OSI Model has them at
two different layers and thus this reference was inaccurate.

Closes-Bug: #1515552

Change-Id: Ia828e3e8d8100a878b6e41ba4f80a24bf5e7d589

commit_message:
Accepts Group IDs from the IdP without domain

Enhance the federation mapping engine to accept
group IDs directly, similarly to how we accept
user IDs directly.

Tried out as per your suggestion although my gut feeling is using e.reason in place of getting traceback info seems wrong. Please check.

Algorithm for this change : 

sys.exc_info() returns a tuple with three values (type, value, traceback).

Here type gets the exception type of the Exception being handled

value is the arguments that are being passed to constructor of exception class

traceback contains the stack information like where the exception occurred etc.

1. If not retry save the rescheduling reason in the instance fault object. Instance fault obj consist of code, message, details. The code always seems to be 500 and the message is nothing but exception reason (e.reason). The details field is calculated based of sys.exc_info() and the code.

Agree with Melanie retry['exc'] comes into play when filter_properties contains retry data. but don't you think 

https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/compute/manager.py#L1922 

will be more better than just dumping e.reason ?"}, {'account_id': 10263, 'date': '2015-10-30 00:51:34.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 20.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-30 02:16:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 20: Verified-1

commit_message:
Omit RescheduledException in instance_fault.message

InstanceFault.message is only String(255) long and exposing "instance ...
was re-scheduled" here displaces the real causes of errors,  and whether
rescheduled or not is a detail that isn't essential for REST API.  Just
omit that so that the real causes can be seen from API.

Co-Authored-By: melanie witt <melwitt@yahoo-inc.com>

Change-Id: I6e3903a3cf8a81607b66deb54c7d5d81cfa704e8
Closes-Bug: 1488332

(2 comments)

@Vilobh, this patch is a good starting point. In overall, what I don't like is calling k8s in objects. Since objects are shared between magnum-api and magnum-conductor. Calling k8s API in objects mean calling k8s in magnum-api, which violates the architectural design (the design is letting conductors to communicate with k8s). Suggest to move all the k8s API call to conductor.

The workflow should be following:

1. Users send requests to controller on all actions (get/post/patch/delete).
2. Controller simply forward the request parameters to conductor.
3. The conductor does the real job: processing the request parameters, calling k8s API, process the response from k8s, send result back to controller.
4. Controller return result to users.

What do you think?"}, {'account_id': 10263, 'date': '2015-09-10 23:45:23.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 10263, 'date': '2015-09-11 00:13:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-14 22:55:36.000000000', 'message': 'Objects from Bay - Replication Controller Creation

Currently objects (pod/rc/service) are read from the database. In
order for native clients to work, they must be read from the
ReST bay endpoint. To execute native clients, we must have one
truth of the state of the system, not two as we do now.

This fix implements it for replication controller creation. If
this approach seems ok, further changes for other resources
read/write path will be made.

Change-Id: I7905af9e22f47b16d92043cc1fdcb1cdf72ebc48
Partially-Implements: bp objects-from-bay

commit_message:
Objects from Bay - Replication Controller

Currently objects (pod/rc/service) are read from the
database. In order for native clients to work, they
must be read from the ReST bay endpoint. To execute
native clients, we must have one truth of the state
of the system, not two as we do now. This patch adds
changes for Replication Controller.

Also, please refer to the related-bug as to the temporary changes
done to make the test work for other objects namely pod,
service. These changes will be removed when the object from bay
patches for all the k8s objects are merged as part of a seperate
patch.

Partially-Implements: bp objects-from-bay
Related-Bug: #1502367
Related-Bug: #1504379

Change-Id: I7905af9e22f47b16d92043cc1fdcb1cdf72ebc48

commit_message:
[Docs] dnsmasq.template fix

1. Removes documentation about manual update of the dnsmasq.template
   file from the Operations guide.
2. Removes the file description from the File reference guide as it
   is autogenerated.

Change-Id: I76bd8b0b2929e447ca61fbdcdb1d7419c2c1a98a
Closes-Bug: #1512342

commit_message:
Only run gate-tempest-dsvm-multinode-live-migration on master

The job requires a hook script from nova which is only in nova master
(mitaka) so don't run this job on any stable branches since it won't
work anyway.

Change-Id: Ib63272a403043e547af893b6c624b08ae0e4b12f

(3 comments)

See a few minor nits inline.

I feel like this is slightly out of scope for the project team guide, which was more about culture and general principles and best practices, rather than a step-by-step project setup guide. That said, I'm not sure we have a better place for that (it does not belong to the CTI, and it does not belong to the Infra guide). An alternative would be to have a project-setup project (like how we use cookiecutter in Python) and recommend using that instead of giving step-by-step instructions. But is it doable/desirable ?

I'm fine with landing this in the project team guide if we don't have better alternatives. I just wanted to open the discussion with other reviewers before we proceed."}, {'account_id': 9717, 'date': '2015-11-17 18:24:55.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 9717, 'date': '2015-11-17 18:39:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I've spoken with the docs team before writing this, they seemed to believe that the Project Team Guide was the best place for this.

I also believe that we have too many different areas of documentation already, and that adding yet another guide is just adding to the noise.

I personally do not have an opinion on where this lives - however I want this discussion to be settled quickly. ttx- if you have an alternative option for where this should live, could you reach out to the docs team and discuss it with them?"}, {'account_id': 9717, 'date': '2015-11-17 18:41:20.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-17 19:15:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

commit_message:
Added project setup guide

This adds a new section, intended to capture common project setup
patterns in greater detail than the governance Consistent Testing
Interface. This change was suggested during discussion of the CTI
patch for npm-based testing available in this patch:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/232756/

Python project guidelines are not yet included, contributions for
such are encouraged in a separate patch.

Change-Id: I00186c9af441c1778a22379634cdb2f918324bd8

commit_message:
Improve handling of corrupted libvirt cache files

Handle more error types when opening cache files, and refreshes
cache files on startup in case unclean restarts resulted in
corrupted files.

Change-Id: I1501e7696a164abefa43c2d43f7c4ed56950a3c3

checks the master branch (by default) but we can also write a
mitaka.rst file asking for version 13.0.0, it should work.

commit_message:
Add reno for release notes management

Since reno is the new tool for Relnotes [1], we need to add it
to Nova and provide some Sphinx docs for Liberty and Mitaka.

Change-Id: Ibd74e62b6f36076dbec17dd146632fd42aad6eb2
(cherry picked from commit 3a65e4848f49c82716713ffc52e30de60957f59b)

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-05 18:09:28.000000000', 'message': "Fix tox not performing some tests under python 3

Many tests are being skipped while testing using tox in py34
environment.
That's because some important environment variables are not defined for
py34 environment.
The variables are:
ZAQAR_TEST_MONGODB=1
ZAQAR_TEST_SLOW=1

This change sets environment variables in tox.ini for py34 environment.

Change-Id: I3a8cef038ed9a37c8dc29850dfdda31b72c05883
Closes-Bug: 1508519
"}, {'created': '2015-11-06 02:11:54.000000000', 'message': "Fix tox not performing some tests under python 3

Many tests are being skipped while testing using tox in py34
environment.
That's because some important environment variables are not defined for
py34 environment.
The variables are:
ZAQAR_TEST_MONGODB=1
ZAQAR_TEST_SLOW=1

This change sets environment variables in tox.ini for py34 environment.

Depends-On: I37937ffe9b71323a92880f678e84c7c24e6872d6

commit_message:
Fix tox not performing some tests in some Envs

Many tests are being skipped while testing using tox in some
environments.
That's because some important environment variables are not defined for
these environments:
pypy, py34.
The variables are:
ZAQAR_TEST_MONGODB=1
ZAQAR_TEST_SLOW=1
This change defines these environment variables in tox.ini. And not only
for the few environments that need such variables, but for all
environments. Because it's the most simple way to do it in which I see
no harm.
Also this change deletes deprecated python environments (py26 and py33)
from the list of environments.

Depends-On: I37937ffe9b71323a92880f678e84c7c24e6872d6
Change-Id: I3a8cef038ed9a37c8dc29850dfdda31b72c05883
Closes-Bug: 1508519

[{'created': '2015-11-12 13:31:20.000000000', 'message': 'Refactor project api and ui make it generic

As part of providing a mechanism to let users group dashboard
information by other run metadata keys (project, voting, etc.), a few
changes were needed both on the ui and api.

On the api, the changes consist on making the endpoint accept any run
metadata key, and not only projects.
On the ui, the changes consist on renaming and adapting ProjectController
to become GroupController: a generic controller that is going to handle this
top-level grouping.

commit_message:
Refactor project api and ui to make them generic

As part of providing a mechanism to let users group dashboard
information by other run metadata keys (project, voting, etc.), a few
changes were needed both on the ui and api.

On the api, the changes consist on making the endpoint accept any run
metadata key, and not only projects.
On the ui, the changes consist on renaming and adapting ProjectController
to become GroupController: a generic controller that is going to handle this
top-level grouping.

Change-Id: Ifde87132b66053b4a86b5d96c337a76e5554713e

commit_message:
Refactor aggregators to use dates in isoformat

There are a few different places where we have been converting dates to
isoformat before sending a response back to UI.
In order to avoid doing that, now the aggregators convert resolved datetime
into iso formatted strings.

Change-Id: I20d0c91b69377d2024af15af642f70a95936d82e

commit_message:
Speed up libvirt cache writes, fix corruption

This patch changes the libvirt cache format from YAML to JSON.  Writing
out the caches in YAML on hosts with a large number of VMs can be slow,
~760ms for 250 VMs, and switching to JSON reduces this write time to
~32ms for the same number of VMs.

The change also removes the _is_cache_corrupt function, replacing it
with improved exception handling.  Testing shows that this change
captures and rebuilds missing, zero-byte, and truncated cache files,
adding a WARNING to the log file if/when either cache is rebuilt.

Change-Id: Ie57dcf4484d4d2d4d8c35a0978275b9c1475db97

commit_message:
Fix write concern check for py34

Mongo client is using None as the default value of write concern.
But in Python 3.x we can't compare by order different types of
operands like in Python 2.x. So after enable py34, test will fail
with below error:

The execution of this boolean expression throws "TypeError:
unorderable types: NoneType() >= int()" when "_mongo_wc"
variable is None.

This patch fixes the issue by adding an additional check.

Closes-Bug: #1513639

Change-Id: I37937ffe9b71323a92880f678e84c7c24e6872d6

commit_message:
Stop discarding exit codes

The return values of both rally and rally-manage were being silently
discarded, so failure was not properly represented to the shell. This
fixes both commands. It appears that the CLI commands already have
proper return values in most (or all) places.

Change-Id: I87d950f8ba8d7f50b604e19e09c44cfbf9066b24

[{'created': '2015-02-10 14:36:20.000000000', 'message': 'Fix for handling L3rpcCallback methods in rpc_worker processes

Split l3_router_plugin setup_rpc method into setup_rpc and start_rpc_listeners
methods and add an rpc_workers_supported method.

In the serve_rpc method of service.py, get all service plugins from the
NeutronManager and pass to the RpcWorker on instantiation.  Then in the
RpcWorker.start() method, call the start_rpc_listeners method on all of
the service plugins.

Closes-Bug: 1419970
Change-Id: Idd7209299c5290424dfe7c2595334d3b2bb58a20

commit_message:
Fix for handling L3rpcCallback methods in rpc_worker processes

Split l3_router_plugin setup_rpc method into setup_rpc and start_rpc_listeners
methods and add an rpc_workers_supported method.

In the serve_rpc method of service.py, get all service plugins from the
NeutronManager (which will include the core plugin) and pass to the RpcWorker
on instantiation.  Then in the RpcWorker.start() method, call the
start_rpc_listeners method on all of the service plugins that have implemented
the start_rpc_listeners method.

Closes-Bug: 1419970
Change-Id: Idd7209299c5290424dfe7c2595334d3b2bb58a20

Client-side changes from Juno to Kilo

This patch makes all the necessary changes to port the labs scripts
from Juno to Kilo.

1. This feature is considered as an improvement of only cli client, and all necessary information about what is it and how to use it completely covered by the few lines of command-line help, so the spec is not required.
If it was about more than extension of an option of an informational command surely it should got a spec.

2. There was no goal to provide filtering at the API side. Client already keep all nodes state inside and already have filtering by labels implemented on its side. My task was to make this filtering more flexible not changing the way its work.

3. Regexp is on its place because:
* It's making only initial tokenisation ("abc=ab xy" => "abc" "=" "ab" "xy") and not processing any nested structures (except strings quotation).
* Any makeshift tokeniser will contain DFA mechanics that already provided by regexp and we just get more code to write and to test.
Moreover regexp is decomposed the way easy to understand (i suppose).'}, {'account_id': 18205, 'date': '2015-11-13 12:01:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Fixing the consequences will take more time than implementing this code."}, {'account_id': 10391, 'date': '2015-11-18 17:17:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-2

Hey Ilya,

Thanks for your contribution. It's nice to see node managements improvements on CLI side. The only concern I have is that we do have this functionality on Web UI side, and you're going to duplicate it there. So any change, any improvement to this functionality on Web UI won't be *automatically* available on CLI side. Moreover, you've forgot about RESTful API users - with this approach they don't have filtering at all (which is bad).

It's a common.. and good practice to implement filtering on backend code, and user backed calls from any client you need (either Web UI or CLI). I believe it shouldn't be a challenge to contribute this code to Nailgun, and use it through CLI."}, {'account_id': 19158, 'date': '2015-11-18 17:35:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Igor, i completely agree with your point except the fact that client-side filtering was introduces earlier than this patch appear. commit_message:
Labels filter expressions is now supported

This change introduce possibility to make requests like these ones:

node list --labels "(label1=val_1 and label2='second value') or not key3"
node list --labels label1 and label2

Closes-bug: #1477605
Change-Id: I43f5542064d5441665b060e18c4776316e23b809

commit_message:
Fix gate-fuel-docs-docs CI job

* Add tox.ini, setup.cfg and setup.py to allow docs building
using tox and setuptools
* Set doc/build as an output dir in setup.cfg to allow doc
publishing by gate-fuel-docs-docs job
* Add '.tox' and '*egg' paths to exclude_patterns in conf.py
* Add stub index.rst with basic info and link to the web verstion
of the docs to fix building of manpages
* Add '.tox' dir to .gitignore

Change-Id: Iaec750d6035bd0e30c10a12142be35514df1fb15
(cherry picked from commit 7218dfecd59b6de18405b42e756b1de2e1d0c8b6)

[{'created': '2015-10-16 11:45:47.000000000', 'message': "Fix error returned when an HA router is updated to DVR

Before this patch, the code compares the 'ha' flag that
comes in from the user, and the current state of the 'distributed'
flag in the DB. This is wrong because if a router is currently
HA in the DB, and the update request contains only
{'distributed': True}, then the 'ha' flag from the request
is None and the error condition is never raised!

The reason the unit tests
(Specifically test_migrate_ha_router_to_distributed)
did not catch this issue is because
of another bug: The _update_router helper method in the L3 HA
unit tests had an 'ha' default value of True, when it should
have had a default value of None. Setting it to None fails
the unit test (Because it raises the wrong exception),
and the contents of the patch makes the unit test pass.

Change-Id: Ie979b6a8400490b578ded17dc6529529e9637b34
Closes-Bug: #1505375
(cherry picked from commit c1f2df2f6b87b435039d4cb52ccb14c0d9c53adc)
"}]
commit_message:
Fix error returned when an HA router is updated to DVR

Before this patch, the code compares the 'ha' flag that
comes in from the user, and the current state of the 'distributed'
flag in the DB. This is wrong because if a router is currently
HA in the DB, and the update request contains only
{'distributed': True}, then the 'ha' flag from the request
is None and the error condition is never raised!

The reason the unit tests
(Specifically test_migrate_ha_router_to_distributed)
did not catch this issue is because
of another bug: The _update_router helper method in the L3 HA
unit tests had an 'ha' default value of True, when it should
have had a default value of None. Setting it to None fails
the unit test (Because it raises the wrong exception),
and the contents of the patch makes the unit test pass.

Change-Id: Ie979b6a8400490b578ded17dc6529529e9637b34
Closes-Bug: #1505375
(cherry picked from commit c1f2df2f6b87b435039d4cb52ccb14c0d9c53adc)

commit_message:
Use reflection.get_class_name() from oslo.utils

oslo.utils is already one dependecy of oslo.service, and we
get method name with reflection.get_callable_name, so we can
get class name with reflection.get_class_name().

Change-Id: I8f61f8def5f1bca7ad14d654c52504c46784b18c

commit_message:
Move 'fill_iter' to 'iter_utils.fill'

This is better placed in the iterator utility module
as it acts on iterables and provides its own iterator
that fills up to (and potentially beyond) a provided
iterator.

Also adds some nice tests to make sure it keeps on
working as expected; as well as tests for other parts
of iter_utils to ensure they keep on working as
expected as well.

Change-Id: Ica90816cbdedfd87f3861a111d7a852655c1fb74

commit_message:
Add route options to neutron router-update

Add the --route and --no-routes options to neutron router-update.

commit_message:
Ensure__repr__ return value is encoded

When __repr__ returns an unicode object, python will
try to encode it with the default encoding scheme
which is ascii in general. So __repr__ needs to make
sure its return value is properly encoded.

Change-Id: Ifdb8c073474a917207a48fc5af5a340e87f66fc4
Closes-Bug: #1514325
(cherry picked from commit f5e792a9833e5139ee1f66b2ac1e55b251c42533)

commit_message:
Matched python and java persister config

Java persister was set to write to InfluxDB every 15 seconds while the Python
persister was set to write every 30 seconds.  15 seconds is a better value when
running the gate jobs.

Change-Id: I5e400d2298cb087dbdfae34458aa4ed2bb1f34b5

commit_message:
Disable clean_nodes by default

This patch sets the conductor/clean_nodes configuration option
for Ironic to False by default. To maintain the same behavior
of the old ramdisk.

The tripleoclient `openstack baremetal introspection bulk`
command needs to be fixed to account for the time it takes
to move from manageable to available in order to have cleaning
turned on by default.

Change-Id: I23c3e7ada3da8085957e86406527e9e5202bdd69
Closes-Bug: 1517449

stack.sh creates a user-specific configuration file ~/.my.cnf for mysql.
If devstack is installed with SERVICE_IP_VERSION=6 option in local.conf,
the IPv6 host address was stored in the ~/.my.cnf file with square
brackets. However mysql does not use bracketing for IPv6 addresses,
resulting in 'Unknown MySQL server host' error when 'mysql' command is

"}]
commit_message:
Remove brackets from IPv6 address in mysql cfgfile

stack.sh creates a user-specific configuration file ~/.my.cnf for mysql.
If devstack is installed with SERVICE_IP_VERSION=6 option in local.conf,
the IPv6 host address was stored in the ~/.my.cnf file with square
brackets. However mysql does not use bracketing for IPv6 addresses,
resulting in 'Unknown MySQL server host' error when 'mysql' command is
run. With this patch IPv6 host address is written to ~/.my.cnf without
brackets.

Closes-Bug: #1516776
Change-Id: I27a7be8c75cf6b09b4a75dc4c9d09cd36bc5ac81

commit_message:
Fix error detection & exit in report_results

We wish to fail if we have >0 zero errors, not >1 errors (i.e. exactly
one error did not trigger a failure!)

This change also brings consistency to the pass & failure paths by
ensuring report_results exits in both cases, since report_results is
supposed to be the last thing run in a test file.

Change-Id: Id4721dffe13721e6c3cd71bca40c3395627e98bf

commit_message:
Use batch 'get_atoms_states' where we can

Instead of doing many single calls to 'get_atom_state' when
we are iterating over many atoms instead prefer to use the
bulk call via 'get_atoms_states' that can gather a large amount
of needed states in a single call, optimizing more of the reading
that taskflow does with regards to states.

This also removes the proxy method 'get_state' from the engine
internal code, since it is no longer needed after this change.

commit_message:
Reduced the complexity of the get_events method

The get_events method is very large - almost 100 lines
(in ceilometer/event/storage/impl_sqlalchemy.py).
I extracted some of the functionalities into helper functions
to reduce the length and complexity of get_events.
Additionally it became more readable as well, without
changing its functionality.

Change-Id: I2eece882b11048a8a02e29954c488daf83d56509

commit_message:
Fix make-changelog target

We need to change targets dependencies to be sure that
make-changelog target will generate "true" packages changelogs
from centos, ubuntu mirrors (without any local rebuilded
packages in chroots)

This patchset introduces less changes, then
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/184116, so we don't need to
change any other dependencies in fuel project

Change-Id: I3aa5b8c1a4aa9918e1fd43caa6d4dd4bedb8b662
Related-bug: #1452284

commit_message:
Fix packages changelog generation

We can have two types of packages changelog:
1. The only packages from mirrors:
  make target: mirror-pkgs-changelog
  should be defined explicitly, for example:

      make iso mirror-pkgs-changelog

  the result will be stored in:
   $(LOCAL_MIRROR)/centos-mirror-packages.changelog
   $(LOCAL_MIRROR)/ubuntu-mirror-packages.changelog

2. Packages from mirrors plus those that were built during
   make iso:
  * docker images;
  * rpm late packages;
  make target will be build automatically during make iso,
  the result will be stored in:
   $(LOCAL_MIRROR)/centos-iso-packages.changelog
   $(LOCAL_MIRROR)/ubuntu-iso-packages.changelog

Change-Id: I4468219cef025658b99315129cd860b00391d16c
Closes-bug: #1452284

commit_message:
Switch debian to openstack-dashboard

The openstack-dashboard-apache package will configure the apache
instance automatically for you and this conflicts with the
configuration done by puppet. This change switches the debian package to
use openstack-dashboard instead of openstach-dashboard so we do not end
up with configuration conflicts between puppet and the packages.

Change-Id: If40c9b308cd040693fd7239c7a063e6a38ff031d

commit_message:
Rename all references of Domain to Zone

This is a pretty invasive change :)

A non complete list of changes:

* Database Tables
* Database Columns
* Designate Objects and fields on Objects
* Designate Objects Adaptors stop doing some of the renames
* All RPCAPI versions are bumped - totally backward
  incompatable (function names have changed)

Change-Id: Ib99e918998a3909fa4aa92bf1ee0475f8a519196

commit_message:
Make CLI Order's type field a required argument

Barbican Secret Order Create has 'type' as an optional parameter,
eventhough it is required. This patch makes the argument a
positional argument.

Change-Id: I5f69ac741ec1d59b7ecb76d6c7cc655a92d18a25
Closes-Bug: #1485615

[{'created': '2015-11-03 14:22:05.000000000', 'message': "Do not run collectstatic or compress in Debian

The Debian packages are handling compress & collectstatic in a
different way as for Ubuntu. This patch avoids running them,
and offload that works to the package.

Note that the variable os_package_type can be defined if we're
using Debian packages on top of Ubuntu (this is achieved by
installing the puppet-openstack-debian-fact package on Ubuntu).
This has been discussed in Tokyo with Emilien.

Change-Id: I3fbb1b576dd61ddd92921e9f12edfe5df21fddd0

commit_message:
Do not run collectstatic or compress in Debian

The Debian packages are handling compress & collectstatic in a
different way as for Ubuntu. This patch avoids running them,
and offload that works to the package. The original collectstatic
indicated that it was a workaround for Debian. See
I813b5f6067bb6ecce279cab7278d9227c4d31d28. Because of this, the
logic around the collectstatic exec has been limited to only
RedHat packaging.

Note that the variable os_package_type can be defined if we're
using Debian packages on top of Ubuntu (this is achieved by
installing the puppet-openstack-debian-fact package on Ubuntu).
This has been discussed in Tokyo with Emilien.

Also, this package fixes the configuration file path for Apache.

Change-Id: I3fbb1b576dd61ddd92921e9f12edfe5df21fddd0
Co-Authored-By: Alex Schultz <aschultz@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Allow tox to be able to run independent functional tests

Allows tox to be able to run all functional tests in a Class as
well as a single functional test. Also runs the tests in verbose
mode, as is done in the gate.

Change-Id: I1fba43aa8c577c81da07522f84cddc36fd7807e1
Closes-Bug: #1514699

commit_message:
Add the debug flag to tox.ini

Allows us to set a breakpoint in code, using pdb.set_trace().
Documentation on how to debug has also been added.
Change-Id: I34bde581ce331b2eb63e4dab08e9f9c597598bf1

commit_message:
Ensure node 'remove' and 'disassociate' can not be called when frozen

When a tree node is frozen it should not be possible to remove nodes
from it or cause that tree node to disassociate itself from its parent,
so make sure that the appropriate decorator is used to ensure this
can not happen (and add tests that verify an exception is raised when
mutations are attempted).

Change-Id: I27e4af7b891ea3fd1826d5a5e71e808ad5af7647

commit_message:
Use conductor entity class constant instead of raw string

Now that the conductor base class provides a constant that
all entity objects produced from it should provide we can
now use that to ensure we are only registering a limited set
of entity kinds.

Change-Id: I0e71a8da64a228fdc68c9de941aaccf54d493d96

commit_message:
log stdout & stderr from executing a command

The command to be executed was being logged. This patch adds
logging for the output of that command: stdout and stderr.

Change-Id: Idb47e131030c6bb7b93d58e67a4e5cda8659e7d7
Closes-Bug: #1514607

commit_message:
Remove duplicated unit tests in test_manager

series because they are duplicates of the tests for

commit_message:
Properly use deployment info in 7.0

In 7.0, default deployment information is returned
for 'ready' nodes and must be used instead of outdated
replaced deployment information.

Closes-bug: 1494507
Closes-bug: 1501728
Change-Id: I545bfabb6c548667464de03fd5aa005d3336002d

commit_message:
Use default gw in admin network for deployment

Set default gw in admin network for isolated deployment of controller, if
defined, otherwise set default gw to master node's ip address.

Change-Id: I0adb9e3b78c29d5fb32ccd60e078fd0fff352647

Can you please elaborate on why this option should be un-depcrecated? Even when it was turned off, the link routes were not getting added and that was the reason why the bug #1335023 was raised. Once when you have the correct behavior i.e. when you can add any gateway (inside the subnet or outside), then there is no relevance for such an option. 

I believe this option should be removed in a future release, and the option should be kept marked as deprecated. If you have a different opinion, I can rebase and remove the deprecation remarks in my patch (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/233287/) as well.

Please let me know how to proceed?'}, {'account_id': 18289, 'date': '2015-11-17 08:32:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Please have a look at the comments from Assaf Muller for bug #1335023
https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1335023

I think there is no relevance to this option, it was forced to True to hide the issue with route creation as in bug #1335023. I've fixed the issue with 'gateway outside the subnet' with patch (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/233287/), and reverted the default value of this option back to False. In a future release this option should be removed all together since there is no meaning for such an option when you can add any gateway the admin prefers. So this option should be kept marked as deprecated.

Do you see any scenario where one would need this option, and to be set to True?
Looking forward for suggestions from all of you."}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-11-18 16:02:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I replied in your patch. I believe now that we have the fix for reference implementation for False value, it's fair to deprecate. I was not aware of your patch, hence decided to unblock that option for those who rely on it when using external routers."}]

commit_message:
Undeprecate force_gateway_on_subnet option

There are valid use cases for gateways outside of subnet range. F.e.
deployers may decide to provide external connectivity in that way, by
injecting link routes.

Change-Id: I18a78adff1106129fd59eaa5be315fcf6ba70cc4

commit_message:
implement is_sahara_enabled

The is_service_enabled method in devstack requires is_sahara_enabled
to be defined somewhere to be used in additional selectors like for
tempest configuration and possibly upgrade work later.

While trying to build a composit job that ran trove / heat / sahara
tests all together this was found to be missing, so sahara never got
configured for tempest.

Change-Id: I69acf6ab2d74d02e9fe8e2d419e54c9367fca500

commit_message:
Pin bashate to 0.3.1

Pin bashate to 0.3.1, and fix up some minor indenting issues

Note we use the same environment override value as in devstack
(I165c4d66db8b7bdcff235ef7d8c99029637bb76a) to allow bashate CI to run
on this.

Change-Id: I0769b1f394643abd0a0b42d571bbb36b8b9c402d

commit_message:
Document release notes process

Since we added support for reno, document that submitters should
provide release notes with their changes. Rather than expecting
others to provide them at the end.

Change-Id: I787f37c9a748774b01cea08da38d91d62de96dd1

subject: Capitalize the first letter of subheadings
messages:
[{'account_id': 17645, 'date': '2015-11-17 08:25:29.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 17645, 'date': '2015-11-17 08:28:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-17 08:35:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-i18n-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/51/246251/2/check/gate-i18n-docs/af92bd8//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 58s'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2015-11-17 08:39:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

I am not sure we need to capitalize all words in titles.

Kato-san, could you share the guidelines of the docs team?
As far as I checked, in documentations under openstack-manuals project, only the first word is capitalized.'}, {'account_id': 17645, 'date': '2015-11-17 08:44:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

please refer to Horizon page http://docs.openstack.org/developer/horizon/contributing.html'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2015-11-17 09:02:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Styling of titles in Horizon documentation looks inconsistent.
I see "Choosing Issues To Work On", "Running the pseudo translation tool", and "JavaScript and CSS libraries". All types of capitalization are used. As Horizon core reviewer, there is no strict convention in Horizon documentation. Someone posted a patch to enforce capitalization,
but there is no consensus and nobody takes care of it much.

I don't have a strong opinion on this, but we need a consensus to avoid this kind of discussion repeatedly.'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2015-11-17 09:03:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

In addition, if we go to this way, let's cleanup all documents!"}, {'account_id': 10497, 'date': '2015-11-17 09:12:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Looks not documented...

But, according to the standard docs team conventions, we do not capitalize unnecessarily to avoid some issues including legal issue. 

Some project might use capital letters. On the other hand, other projects use small letters.

For example: http://docs.openstack.org/contributor-guide/

Is capitalization important?'}, {'account_id': 17645, 'date': '2015-11-17 10:23:07.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

It seems that capitalize subheading not that important'}, {'account_id': 17645, 'date': '2015-11-18 01:32:22.000000000', 'content': 'Restored'}, {'account_id': 17645, 'date': '2015-11-18 01:34:42.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

Capitalize the first letter of subheadings

 It is better to capitalize and it looks consistent with other
 document pages

Change-Id: Ic1752031feb573f363d2307edc3ac9000d478556

commit_message:
Remove SysV init script for neutron-server

The script has some issues, f.e. it does not read any plugin
configuration file.

I don't believe anyone relies on it these days. The only distro I could
think of that could use it is Debian, but they have their own version of
the script maintained independently.

So it seems easier to remove it not to mislead users.

Change-Id: Ice622402a6261cfed8a8b042d732f39e25aff77c

commit_message:
Update docstrings on entity type

Describe the instance variables and there types with
docstrings and comments and such, so that it is more
known what this type is for.

Also removes docstring saying this is only for jobs
and jobboards since it is really a more generic entity
class and has no direct tie to jobboards.

Change-Id: I98adb161adcb4ce096c1ee0e6c3377eb71383a90

commit_message:
Move base.py and config.py under unit/ folder

base.py and config.py files are used only in unit tests, but
now they are located near unit and functional tests folder, so
it seems that they are used in functional tests too.

Change-Id: Iedefb76a065d3155065be8e2a3a11bcf4b9dc69d

In theory we can. However It also has its cons and I thing in this particular case they are prevail on pros

Pros:
1) UI form becomes consistent with property names

Cons:
1) Application backward compatibility breaks
2) Application need to be retested because it is easy to rename something wrong. It is not enough to rename property and we don't have any tools for automatic refactoring

Also google still calls them minions in many places in k8s code. So IMO nothing wrong if we also do"}, {'account_id': 7226, 'date': '2015-11-12 01:35:58.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-12 01:36:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Fixing wf execution creation at initial stage

 * Wf execution is not created when first
   task(s) failed.
 * Fixed some unit-tests.

Closes-Bug: #1506470

Change-Id: Id34b11efe15fcff0a9360e2966d1a85c29325c62
(cherry picked from commit e0c00aa51634d84bed5a3bdbe07339bafc56979f)

commit_message:
Add reno for release notes management

Mostly cargo-culted from I9549e6b491b26232f4dac900b0bf05f10eb0e30a.

Note that reno automatically inserts version numbers; liberty.rst is
sufficient for intermediate release models.

This is backported to stable/liberty by request in
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-November/078940.html

Change-Id: Ic700d719242b17532b0b43a68b7eff507cb3a43c
(cherry picked from commit aae12e5109dcff35a72f111d9ef5d72157d589c6)

commit_message:
libvirt: mlnx_direct vif type removal

The mlnx_direct vif_type is deprecated from Juno release. sriov-nic-switch
vif_type with macvtap vnic_type it the replacement for mlnx_direct.
This patch removes the mlnx_direct vif_type related code.

Closes-Bug: #1453410

Change-Id: I0f63e8eeb19de7bbcf817d27181b75946101430b

commit_message:
Stop using uuid in functional tests

Some functional tests were using the uuid library for unique
names. The testing framework provides us a method, getUniqueString(),
for just such a thing, so we should use that instead.

Change-Id: I08b8ef91b9cd467ade9fac1a73a5bd8976e207ed

commit_message:
Bug fix while editing actions with missing keys

If a key is not present in the database, the panel failed to open the modal
windows for edition, this fix that by using the dict.get()

Change-Id: Ic5f5e216828f10d41f288408fc5109dc004c6ab7

commit_message:
[Ironic] Add transformations for Ironic

This change introduces L2 transformations for baremetal network
and L3 neutron network.

Change-Id: I565c703dca6cedaa74f0bf426d82ecde79257ecb
Implements: blueprint fuel-integrate-ironic (partially)

commit_message:
WIP [Security] Hide confidential information in logs

This patch is just for discussion about whether we should go ahead with
the fix, to make sure we go the right direction.

Closes-Bug: #1337268

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-05 13:00:03.000000000', 'message': 'Fix BUILD_PACKAGES flag

Build iso with BUILD_PACKAGES=0:

* Late packages:
  - fuel-bootstrap-image,
  - fuel-docker-images,
  should be always build in spite of  BUILD_PACKAGES flag,
  since they are depend on the first level artifacts (packages)
  and are not in the mirrors yet;

* fuel matapackage can be added only after putting all
  dependencies to upstream mirror

* Update requirements-*.txt files with adding all fuel packages

Related-bug: #1460480

Change-Id: I00ea15c9df9277d48a294f8379d87352c017becb

commit_message:
Fix BUILD_PACKAGES flag

Build iso with BUILD_PACKAGES=0:

* Late packages:
  - fuel-bootstrap-image,
  - fuel-docker-images,
  should be always built in spite of  BUILD_PACKAGES flag,
  since they depend on the first level artifacts (packages)
  and are not updated in the mirrors yet;

* Build fuel-bootstrap-image-builder package for astute container

* Update requirements-*.txt file by adding all fuel packages only in case
  BUILD_PACKAGES=0

* Update docker-images spec to support fakeroot rpmbuild approach

Related-bug: #1460480

Change-Id: I00ea15c9df9277d48a294f8379d87352c017becb

Fix missing policy.json in Magnum

The magnum api falls over on a request without this file in place

commit_message:
Use get_interface_bridge instead of get_bridge_for_tap_device

bridge_lib defines get_interface_bridge which returns the bridge on
which an interface is connected (or None) where LB L2-agent[1] returns
it only if the bridge is a bridge managed by LB L2-agent.

According to get_bridge_for_tap_device 1st usage:

  if bridge_lib.is_bridged_interface(interface):
     bridge = self.get_bridge_for_tap_device(interface)
     bridge.delif(interface)

The code crashs if interface is owned by a non-LB-agent bridge because
the condition is verified but bridge is None.

[1] neutron.plugins.ml2.drivers.linuxbridge.agent.linuxbridge_neutron_agent

Partial-Bug: #1514548
Change-Id: If6dba1197b3f08ecc0ac01fcf085c8268f81169f

commit_message:
Add more 'actions' for server concepts doc

commit cf44f0ab7d89784f5ac231b20ec99e3b540b7aa3 add server
concepts for the servers, some TODOs for other actions,
this patchs add the items.
Some comments are copied from support matrix doc
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/nova/support-matrix.html
which mainly talked about virt layer support while this doc more
talk about server concepts.

Partially implements blueprint complete-todo-in-api-concept-doc

Change-Id: I08c97c78b334bd17b37492ac60a7489ac6fe07de

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-11-10 02:24:06.000000000', 'message': "Python3: fix glance.tests.unit.v2.test_registry_client

Some issues:
- the usual str vs bytes thing;
- 'reload' no longer exists in Python 3, but is available through six;
- 'min_ram' has to be an integer because Python 3 cannot compare
  integers and strings.

commit_message:
Python3: fix glance.tests.unit.v2.test_registry_client

Some issues:
- the usual str vs bytes thing;
- 'reload' no longer exists in Python 3, but is available through six;
- 'min_ram' and 'min_disk' have to be integers because Python 3 cannot
  compare integers and strings.

Change-Id: I8a65da8bad7ba14b6af32348c30366d0db49212c

Add test cases for CDH plugin versionfactory

[{'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-11-11 21:14:24.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-11-11 21:14:38.000000000', 'content': 'Topic changed from bp/s to process'}, {'account_id': 13995, 'date': '2015-11-11 21:34:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

(1 comment)

Good stuff, but there was one sentence that had some nits.  Not throwing the -1 for them though, because the meaning comes through.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-11 21:42:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

- gate-neutron-pep8-constraints http://logs.openstack.org/13/244313/1/check/gate-neutron-pep8-constraints/4206b8d/ : SUCCESS in 4m 37s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-11-11 21:43:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Why are we trying to simplify this so much? Is it too hard to understand the 4 levels that are currently used? Who is having problems with this? Or is the problem that people can't understand how things map somehow?"}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-11-11 22:57:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

@Kyle: it's not that it's too hard to understand the four (out of total 6 levels) of priorities. It's the fact that we lack the criteria to define the priority buckets. If we can come up with criteria (and consensus) for all four priorities, then fine I am happy to keep them; but I think it's a lot easier to manage with two...the classification is a lot easier. Another extreme simplification would be to get rid of priorities altogether, assuming that we want to work on everything at the same pace and at the same level of priority. The reality is that the pace is dictated by the level of attention that core reviewers give to patches, and history has demonstrated that some of us (I certainly do) work with two speeds  (I either give my fully devoted attention to a feature or I don't)."}, {'account_id': 8124, 'date': '2015-11-11 23:16:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-11-11 23:22:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 7776, 'date': '2015-11-12 00:25:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I agree that for any one person there are really only three priorities, "I'm working on it" or "I'm not working on it right now" or "I'm not going to work on it" and the third one doesn't warrant a status. However, is Neutron just one person? This limitation to two priorities makes sense if everything is either "all hands on deck" or "nobody is working on it".'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-11-12 02:19:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Paul: one of the criteria to determine features' priorities is human resource allocation and availability, but that's possibly the worst one we could choose from in openstack as we have no collective control of people's schedules and agendas.

I hope I didn't give the impression that I had that in mind when I put this proposal forward."}, {'account_id': 6524, 'date': '2015-11-12 04:11:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-11-12 07:18:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 11307, 'date': '2015-11-12 07:24:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2015-11-12 07:26:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

(1 comment)

I agree this simplifies the thing and it is a good start.
Even if it turns out we still need more priorities, we have more priorities between them.'}, {'account_id': 6788, 'date': '2015-11-12 10:21:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I like simplifications and order. I have only one concern. I imagine high priority blueprints are going to be worked on mostly by core devs, for two reasons because they are essential to the project so if there are no volunteers a core would take it and because they are usual pretty complex so you need to be familiar with Neutron. Most of the low priority blueprints are going to be proposed and worked on by other members of the community. They won't get much attention and probably won't get merged. This would reinforce the idea that "it's hard to get code in Neutron", "you need to be part of the inner circle to get code in". We know that we don't have enough bandwidth for everything but setting the low status straight away would make the idea "only cores get code in" seems almost official and would immediately discourage new contributors. That's my fear. Can we introduce a medium level for blueprints that are not essential but have people that want to work on it? We can then have stricter rules, for example if you don't contribute to the blueprint for a month then priority will be lowered.'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2015-11-12 12:19:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-11-12 13:54:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I don't doubt having two priorities is easier. I also agree that people tend to work in two speeds: Full speed or full stop. However, I personally think it's worth taking some time expand on what the 4 priorities mean and keep them. Moving to two priorities to me just punts the problem a bit, and if we're going to two, then we might as well move to a single one."}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-11-12 17:38:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Here is what I suggest we look at making the existing 4 priorities:

Essential: The entire core team agrees this is essential for the release.

High: A majority of the core team agrees this is essential for the release.

Low: Vendor items or things which are not essential for the release.

Medium: Everything else

Now, after typing this, I'm more inclined to just dump this and put everything as High, going with a single priority."}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-11-12 18:19:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)

@Rossella: if I gave the impression that high and low are 2 classes of citizens, then I need to rephrase because it's not my intention. The whole point of the changes that I have been trying to make over the last month or so is to ensure we can a) have more predictability of what we deliver; and b) have better visibility in how we make decisions.

That has nothing to do with how we make task assignment. Low priority items will and must be worked/supported by core as much as high priority efforts, but they are to be seen as improvements of the platform that are not directly fixing a 'broken' element of the project.

So to give you an instance (and let's not fixate on the specific example): rolling upgrades...that's to me is High, because without it the pain caused is great. but enabling QOS in Linux Bridge...that to me is Low, because it's nice to have, but without it, I will still be able to spin up VM's and possibly have some workaround in place to achieve what I need to achieve (bandwidth guarantee)."}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-11-12 18:25:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Kyle: I clearly got misunderstood. This has nothing to do with resource assignment. Your breakdown tells me that we can cut to 3, because we no longer track vendor items by design. As for Essential and High: I can't see why the core team wouldn't have universal agreement on assigning priority. So that's one of the reasons why I could think we could get away with 2.

That said, you haven't really given me a set of criteria, have you? You defined essential as a subjective matter and used a majority voting to distinguish from high; I don't recall I was ever asked to contribute to priority settings.

This is what I am trying to fix, I am trying to give a clear set if indications to judge on work items, so that the process is also consistent from release to release, from PTL to PTL, etc."}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-11-12 18:25:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

I'll respin taking into account of the existing feedback."}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-11-12 18:27:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Armando, I was indicating how perhaps things could be now, not how they were before. Before, no one honestly cared about priorities ... unless it was their own stuff. Fundamentally, this is the problem! I could never figure out a way to get people to review stuff that actually mattered. Now, I never tried offering donuts or cookies, perhaps that was the trick. But I would argue we're never gonna figure that out. So, we might as well just dump these priorities and go with the model of "It's in or it's out", and if it's in, it's low priority, and everything is low priority.'}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-11-12 18:29:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

On second thought, I think this approach of "High" vs "Low" is really "in vs out" already.

So +2.'}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-11-12 18:31:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Awaiting a new spin to understand better.

-1 is purely for my review stats.'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-11-12 21:01:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-11-12 22:44:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Kyle, if it's just for stats collection, can I +2-2+1-1 my own patch? Or would that be frowned upon?"}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-11-12 22:48:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-11-12 22:49:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

The coolest part about Kyle's comment is: it's not 100% clear whether he is trolling. For Armando's one, there is no doubt about it.

Good job Kyle!"}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2015-11-12 23:42:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

I like this. It's a change that reflects reality. We'd like to improve the project, we'd like to set priorities, but given that this is an open source project, our PTL does not have free reign to assign people to tasks. That's just reality. There is no meaning to scrubbing dozens of RFEs and prioritizing them because there are no resources to assign. We can, however, mark RFEs that the core team would appreciate if they were to go in. Having two priorities is basically saying, there are no priorities, apart from this bucket of RFEs over here that's really nice and shiny and would really benefit from some review attention."}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-11-13 01:32:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

After 3 cycles of being PTL, I've gained "Gerrit Cloaking, level 10" as a skill Ihar. Now if only I could acquire the "+3 button of inevitable code" I'd be able to gain a level!

If you get that reference, you're as old or older than me, and also an incredible geek.

I <3 gerrit.

:)'}, {'account_id': 7776, 'date': '2015-11-13 03:17:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

I'm ok with this, it's probably close enough to reality. However, I think there might actually be three real levels:

 lowest -> "it's nobody's top priority, not getting done"
 middle -> "it's somebody's top priority"
 highest -> "it's blocking everybody from doing anything"

Anything that anyone is actively writing code for should be approximately equal regardless of core vs non-core. The reason for bumping something up higher is that it's so broken that it's blocking everything, not just because it isn't the top priority of a core.'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-11-13 04:54:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Paul: I don't understand why we would be tracking something we're not going to deliver!"}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-11-13 09:18:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

"We can, however, mark RFEs that the core team would appreciate if they were to go in"

@Assaf, I actually don't see that in the proposal since all RFEs are just bugs with Wishlist state. Armando replied that it's ok because RFEs without BPs mean 'RFEs that are no-brainers' and hence will get enough attention to go in, if really critical. Not sure it's always the case [there can be a no-brainer like oslo config generator adoption that sits there for cycles], but I guess I just miss something.'}, {'account_id': 7776, 'date': '2015-11-13 15:59:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Armando: I should have said "not getting done right now" meaning I agree with your assessment that it it's not a top priority for somebody then it's not likely to be making any progress at all because for any one person they're working on something 100% and everything else very close to 0%.

Where I may disagree with you is on whether there needs to be collective agreement. I think there are probably a small number of things that need to be everybody's top priority because they block all other progress, a large number of things that are somebody's top priority but may not matter at all to most people, and then a backlog of things that will be somebody's top priority sometime in the future but aren't anybody's top priority right now. I think something can be high priority if it's somebody's top priority even if it isn't considered high priority collectively by all core folks.'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-11-13 16:24:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Paul: what I am trying to move away from is the association between 'collective agreement' and priority, because to me that's something highly subjective. Everyone has his/her own agenda and what's high for me is not high for you. My attempt here is to move to a direction where priorities can be assessed based on a set of objective criteria, so that we have priorities assessed consistently across releases and across the evolutions of the team (people come and go). I don't want this project to work like a politics where a party (when in government) brings its own agenda, only to be steered in a different direction by the opposition when it becomes their turn."}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-11-13 16:27:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Ihar: oslo generator might have fallen through the cracks..but that was the old world. I am trying to usher a 'brave new world'...and now I challenge Kyle to figure out the reference!"}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-11-13 20:24:03.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-11-13 20:24:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Elaborate how priorities are assigned to blueprints

Prioritizing is hard, and prioritizing in open source, let
alone Openstack, is even harder.

For this reason, this proposal attempts to clarify what priority
mean, how we prioritize in Neutron, in a way that's objective,
consistent, and reproducible. To start with, and make things slightly
simpler, we reduce the number of priority buckets we can choose from
to two: High and Low.

The way priorities are assigned is then based on a set of clearly defined
criteria: high priority work items are items that all core folks
collectively should care about because any failure in achieving tangible
result make them look bad. Low work items are great to have, but if they
slipped, it would be a shame but not the end of the world.

Keep on reading to learn more.

Change-Id: I0f4ba622eb3d8e02b0c3204967fb8eae22db09c8

I don't think we should encourage use of:


@utils.synchronized('{volume_id}-{f_name}', external=True)


for any method needing to be decorated with a lock.  This is too complicated to read and grep for, and will lead to people mixing things up.

It may make sense to use this technique to define names like @locked_volume_id_operation, but please don't change use of decorators to this style."}, {'account_id': 15831, 'date': '2015-09-15 15:41:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

- infortrend-cinder-volume-iscsi http://openstack.infortrend.com/58/217258/6/check/infortrend-cinder-volume-iscsi/7bbbb96 : SUCCESS in 2h 35m 11s
- infortrend-cinder-volume-fc http://openstack.infortrend.com/58/217258/6/check/infortrend-cinder-volume-fc/74e2667 : SUCCESS in 2h 41m 17s'}, {'account_id': 12825, 'date': '2015-09-16 17:51:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(1 comment)

@Eric so in your opinion each function that need a lock, should have a separate decorator, that specify lock name somewhere inside it and will be used once in entire code base? I don't see how it's less complicated.
About readability - python string formatting is pretty easy to read IMO. 

So please compare

 def locked_volume_operation(f):
    """..."""
    def lvo_inner1(inst, context, volume_id, **kwargs):
        @utils.synchronized("%s-%s" % (volume_id, f.__name__), external=True)
        def lvo_inner2(*_args, **_kwargs):
            return f(*_args, **_kwargs)
        return lvo_inner2(inst, context, volume_id, **kwargs)
    return lvo_inner1
 ...
 @locked_volume_operation
 def delete_volume(...)

with

 @utils.synchronized('{volume_id}-{f_name}', external=True)
 def delete_volume(...)

and tell me what part of second expression you found more complicated, especially when you want to check what will be the actual lock name.'}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2015-09-17 15:34:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

That's not the right comparison, the comparison is

 @locked_volume_operation
 def delete_volume(...)

vs

 @utils.synchronized('{volume_id}-{f_name}', external=True)
 def delete_volume(...)

I'm fine with @locked_volume_operation being changed to use format strings this way.  But asking everyone to remember how to correctly use format strings throughout their drivers makes it a lot easier to break things, and it's harder to read.

People shouldn't have to think through details like whether they want "external" or not when trying to add locking to a method.  Defining standard lock names solves that complexity.

I'm also not saying that different methods need different decorators.  We are already using @locked_volume_id_operation across five different driver files.

As a separate note, I don't think this approach works for something like @locked_volume_id_operation which can handle both volume and snapshot objects automatically, so there are restrictions brought on by forcing use of format strings:

http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/cinder/tree/cinder/volume/drivers/remotefs.py?id=a765b1#n106'}, {'account_id': 12825, 'date': '2015-09-18 14:26:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

First and foremost, as you can clearly see this patch only applies changes to volume manager decorators where, as mentioned, very similar lock decorators was used once per function. Example provided was adequate, you cannot compare those two implementations without presenting corresponding decorators definitions. If you still are not convinced consider following situations:
* you want to lock execution of another function in volume manager - with current implementation you would create just another locking decorator with implementation almost identical to previous 3
* you want to know what will be the actual name of the lock used - currently you need to check individual decorators implementations

> But asking everyone to remember how to correctly use format strings throughout their drivers makes it a lot easier to break things, and it's harder to read.

Basic Python knowledge is required to contribute to OpenStack - https://docs.python.org/2/library/string.html#formatstrings

> People shouldn't have to think through details like whether they want "external" or not when trying to add locking to a method. 

You should think through details of each method that you are implementing and know exactly what kind of lock you need wen you plan to use it.

> I'm also not saying that different methods need different decorators. 

In volume manager different methods need different decorators.

> We are already using @locked_volume_id_operation across five different driver files.

I know very well about existence of remotefs.locked_volume_id_operation, implementation of this patch is based on it after all.

> I don't think this approach works for something like @locked_volume_id_operation which can handle both volume and snapshot objects automatically

It may handle those two cases well, but what if you want lock name based on snapshot id or any other parameter? You create another decorator?'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-13 04:53:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change or one of its cross-repo dependencies was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of its repository. Please rebase the change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 12825, 'date': '2015-11-18 13:58:09.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Obsolete. Replaced by https://review.openstack.org/#/c/183537'}]

commit_message:
utils.synchronized lock name formatting

This patch simplifies usage of locks, which name depends on
value of parameters passed to function decorated by
utils.synchronized.

Change-Id: I95b204acb46d193782f256d34e13dd77840489b0

[{'created': '2015-10-09 12:58:47.000000000', 'message': 'Factor up config dependent credential classes

Separate helpers methods to build credentials, credential providers and
client managers that depend on configuration. They are all moved to
the common.credentials module to achieve two objectives:
- prepare credential provider module to move to tempest-lib
- avoid circular dependencies

There are still dependencies to CONF in the credential providers,
removing all of them would make the patch too large; but there is
with this patch a single place where all relevant CONF parameters can
be looked up and passed into the credential providers.

commit_message:
Factor up config dependent credential classes

Separate helpers methods to build credentials, credential providers and
client managers that depend on configuration. They are all moved to
the common.credentials module to achieve two objectives:
- prepare credential provider module to move to tempest-lib
- avoid circular dependencies

There are still dependencies to CONF in the credential providers,
removing all of them would make the patch too large; but there is
with this patch a single place where all relevant CONF parameters can
be looked up and passed into the credential providers.

Partially-implements: bp tempest-library
Change-Id: I351f86f0570070105bbf24f2d904e917feea6e57

commit_message:
Release Notes for 0.17.3

ffd135c Updated from global requirements
fab2ace Updated from global requirements
68cf63d Don't get the image before deleting it
15fe21d Updated from global requirements
e7a801d Ship the default image schema in the client
320bc6f V2: Do not validate image schema when listing
0acf7cc Expose 'is_base' schema property attribute

Change-Id: Icc2f9108276747ea6324e410d56c7b73f1048562
